The variants of this vignette read as follows: This story is about a boy named Andy. Andy has found a frog in his yard. Now, Andy loves frogs. A girl in Andy’s neighborhood named Nicole [positive: loves frogs too; negative: hates frogs; neutral: has never seen a frog before]. Andy wants to bring the frog over to Nicole’s house. If he brings the frog over, she will [positive: be happy; negative: get upset; neutral: see a frog for the first time]. Andy says, “I don’t care that Nicole will [positive: be happy; negative: get upset; neutral: see a frog for the first time]. I am going to bring the frog over because I want to.” So Andy brings the frog over to Nicole’s house and she [positive: is happy; negative: gets upset; neutral: sees a frog for the first time]. Two additional vignettes were created: one featured a child playing a CD that causes another child to be happy, get upset, or tap her foot; and one featured a child who tells ghost stories that cause another child to be happy, get upset, or fall asleep. Because distinctions in moral reasoning between individuals with and without psychopathic traits are most likely to emerge in the context of victim distress, the consequence of all the negatively valenced scenarios was a child becoming upset.

qmeasure3_e:
We examined these intuitions adopting the structure of Nahmias, Coates, and Kvaran’s (2007) scenarios to
create psychologically non-reductionistic real world concrete scenarios. These scenarios are identical to the psychologically
non-reductionistic real world abstract scenarios except that the second paragraph is replaced with the following paragraph:
So, once specific earlier events have occurred in a person’s life, these events will definitely cause specific later events to
occur. For example, one day a person named John decides to kill his wife so that he can marry his lover, and he does it.
Once the specific thoughts, desires, and plans occur in John’s mind, they will definitely cause his decision to kill his wife.
We used this version for three reasons. First, it involves a socially important action of a man killing his wife. Second, it
describes determinism in terms of complete causation while at the same time avoiding using terminology implying that
events had to happen as they did.8 Third, we know that in the psychologically non-reductionist, concrete scenarios the majority
of people have compatibilist intuitions (Nahmias et al., 2007, p. 230).
qmeasure4_e:
Most respected neuroscientists [psychologists] are convinced that eventually we will figure out exactly how all of our
decisions and actions are entirely caused. For instance, they think that whenever we are trying to decide what to do,
the decision we end up making is completely caused by the specific chemical reactions and neural processes [thoughts,
desires, and plans] occurring in our brains [minds]. The neuroscientists [psychologists] are also convinced that these
chemical reactions and neural processes [thoughts, desires, and plans] are completely caused by our current situation
and the earlier events in our lives, and that these earlier events were also completely caused by even earlier events, eventually
going all the way back to events that occurred before we were born.
So, if these neuroscientists [psychologists] are right, then once specific earlier events have occurred in a person’s life,
these events will definitely cause specific later events to occur. For instance, once specific chemical reactions and neural
processes [thoughts, desires, and plans] occur in the person’s brain [mind], they will definitely cause the person to make
the specific decision he or she makes (Nahmias, Coates, & Kvaran, 2007, p. 224).

So, once specific earlier events have occurred in a person’s life, these events will definitely cause specific later events to
occur. For example, one day a person named John decides to kill his wife so that he can marry his lover, and he does it.

goals1_e: Our empirical study was undertaken with three goals in mind. The rst was to determine whether non-philosophers share the intuition that protagonists in fake-barn cases do not have knowledge – we’ll call it the ‘philosophically popular’ intuition.2 The second was to examine whether the number of fakes that a protagonist in a fake-barn style thought experiment has been exposed to affects participants’ willingness to attribute knowledge. The third goal was to explore a demographic variable, age, which has been largely ignored by experimental philosophers interested in epistemology
goals2_e: If participants share the philosophically popular intuition, we would expect to nd a signicant difference between responses to the knowledge question in the knowledge conditions (which we take to involve clear cases of knowledge) and in the fake-barn conditions. If knowledge attribution is more likely to be undermined when a protagonist has already encountered a large number of potential defeaters rather than none at all, we should also expect to nd a signicant difference between the low-defeaters and highdefeaters conditions. Finally, for the reasons discussed in the introduction, we hypothesized that age may inuence knowledge attribution in this kind of case.
goals3_e: While other studies have investigated the relationship between epistemic intuitions and such demographic variables as ethnicity (Weinberg et al. 2001; Nichols et al. 2003; Waterman et al. ms) and gender (Buckwalter and Stich 2013), there has been no experimental work looking at the impact of age on epistemic intuitions.

interpretation_e: s. First, this study might be interpreted as showing that lay people share the philosophically popular intuition about fake-barn cases since there is a statistically signicant difference between the knowledge and fake-barn conditions. Knowledge attribution is higher in the knowledge conditions (where no potential defeaters exist) than in the fake-barn conditions (where potential defeaters do exist). However, the difference between knowledge and fake-barn conditions is much smaller than what one would expect in light of the philosophically popular intuition. Moreover, since all mean values were signicantly above the mid-point on the Likert scale, it would appear that non-philosophers are inclined to attribute knowledge in all these conditions. Caution is needed here since there are legitimate questions about how the mid-point of a Likert scale should be interpreted in experimental philosophy (Cullen 2010), but, if we do interpret responses that are higher than the mid-point as attributions of knowledge, and if our ndings are indicative of how non-philosophers would react to these and other fake-barn style cases, then non-philosophers do not share the philosophically popular intuition. This conclusion ts well with previous critical discussion of the philosophically popular intuition. In particular, Gendler and Hawthorne have argued that ‘the concept of knowledge ... never offered any stable negative verdict in the original fake barn case’ (2005: 348), although they did not include age, or any other demographic factors, among the potential causes of this lack of stability.

interpretation_e: In addition, these results go beyond those reported by May, by demonstrating that Consciousness is a third, independent factor relevant to free will attribution.
validity_e:
1. Filling that explanation out, however, requires far more than these results show.

 

2. I turn to a different issue. The fact that application of the concept of free will is driven by Ensurance, Liberty, and Consciousness might be taken to conflict with a recent theory of free will attribution. Murray and Nahmias (2014) argue that most people lack intuitions in favor of incompatibilism, and that attributions of free will that appear incompatibilist can be explained by way of an error theory. According to Murray and Nahmias, nonphilosophers misinterpret descriptions of determinism as implying bypassing of those (conscious) mental states, events, and processes normally thought to be relevant for free action. When reading vignettes regarding action in deterministic universes, non-philosophers falsely infer that an agent’s mental states, events, and processes “have no causal effect” on their behavior (2014: 440). If Murray and Nahmias are right, one would predict different results than those found here. First, one would predict that Liberty would not have an effect independent of that produced by Consciousness. For, once the causal importance of Consciousness is properly emphasized, one would think that most participants would not be inclined to mistake determinism for bypassing. Second, one would predict that participants attributing low levels of free will in deterministic, non-conscious scenarios would tend to blame the absence of Consciousness, rather than the absence of Liberty. But this is not what we find. Instead, we find that participants cite Liberty as important to their judgment at significantly higher rates when cases involve determinism, even when these cases also emphasize the absence of Consciousness.

 

3. The enterprising compatibilist might make a case that the importance of Ensurance—as I have operationalized it—provides an intuitive strand in our concept of free will upon which absence of luck arguments can build. For the enterprising compatibilist, then, the proper concept of free will may turn out to be compatibilist, once we have cleansed the folk concept of its undesirable incompatibilist elements.

Testing this empirical hypothesis con
stitutes
the central goal of this article: We present the first experimental
studies about whether the intentionality ascriptions of professional
judges manifest an outcome effect. French judges were chosen since in
France laypeople juries are extremely rare and nearly all criminal trials
are decided by professionals.
conceptual1_e:
On this
view, intentionality involves both a cognitive element, i.e. awareness or

recruitment1_e:
36 professional French judges (23 of whom were female) completed an unpaid online questionnaire. About three times as many were contacted
directly via email. Sample size was determined by the number of
judges who responded to the invitation and filled out the questionnaire.
All complete data sets were used. 26 judges served at a jurisdiction de
première instance (the lowest type of court), 9 at a cour d’appel (court of
appeal) and 1 as conseiller juridique (legal advisor). 24 participants listed
criminal law as their speciality, 17 civil law, 5 social law, and 1 administrative
law and 7 other specialities (multiple answers possible).
The average professional experience was just under 17 years, ranging
from less than a year to 37 years. The native language of all participants
was French, nobody stated familiarity with the Knobe effect and only
one participant stated familiarity with experimental philosophy.

preregistration_e:
• No mention of “pre-registration,” “registered,” “registration,” or similar terms appears in the main text, footnotes, appendices, or acknowledgments.

  • The authors do not reference any registry (e.g., OSF, AsPredicted, or a university repository).
materials_availability_e:
Appendix 1

  • The paper includes verbatim text of all four vignettes used in the study:

    • Coinflip Dave

    • Truetemp Charles

    • Fakebarn Suzy

    • Chemist Karen

  • These are presented in full in the Appendix 1: Epistemological Intuitions Survey, with the exact wording of the stimuli and the Likert-scale response options.
data_availability_e: Although the article summarizes some descriptive statistics (e.g., means, standard deviations, ANOVA results), these are not sufficient to reconstruct the full raw data at the participant level.
conclusions_comment:
• Instability of Intuitions (Contextual Sensitivity):

    • The authors address the instability of intuitions, particularly how intuitions about the Truetemp Case can vary depending on the order in which other thought-experiments are presented. This raises a construct validity concern about whether the intuitions measured in the study reflect the intended construct or if they are influenced by extraneous factors like the order of presentation.

  • Order Effects:

    • The study's design includes an order effect (how the sequence of thought-experiments influences responses). This also questions whether the study's operations are truly capturing participants' intuitions in an isolated manner, as the results might be influenced by the order in which stimuli are presented. This is another construct validity concern because the order effect may be confounding the measurement of the intended construct (epistemic intuitions).

  • Exclusion of Professional Philosophers:

    • The study uses a sample of non-philosophers, which raises an objection about whether the study is properly measuring intuitions in the relevant target population. This could be viewed as a construct validity threat because if professional philosophers have different intuitions than the general population, the study may not be measuring the construct (epistemic intuitions) in the way it was intended.
background1_e:
The authors clearly articulate a research problem in the abstract and introduction. Specifically, they investigate:

“whether intuitions in response to Lehrer’s Truetemp Case vary depending on whether, and which, other thought experiments are considered first.”

They position this within the broader problem of the reliability of philosophical intuitions, especially those used as evidence in epistemology, and suggest that order effects may undermine the evidential value of such intuitions. This is an identifiable, empirically testable question situated within ongoing debates in epistemology and experimental philosophy.
background2_e:
The paper discusses a theoretical dispute in epistemology, specifically the debate over reliabilism as a theory of knowledge. Lehrer’s Truetemp Case is used to argue against reliabilism by suggesting that a belief formed via a reliable process (in this case, through a brain implant) might still not qualify as knowledge due to lack of awareness or justification.

The authors explore whether intuitions about this case—often used as evidence against reliabilism—are stable or susceptible to contextual framing effects (i.e., which cases are considered first). This connects their empirical work directly to a significant philosophical debate, making the research problem theoretically relevant.
background3_e:
The paper includes a clear and substantive review of previous empirical and philosophical work:

  • It references prior empirical studies showing that philosophical intuitions vary with cultural background, educational level, socio-economic status, and affective framing (e.g., Weinberg, Nichols & Stich; Machery et al.; Nichols & Knobe).

  • It also outlines how philosophers traditionally rely on intuitions in evaluating thought experiments and discusses the use of the Truetemp Case in arguments against reliabilism.

  • Furthermore, the authors position their study as an extension of existing experimental philosophy literature, emphasizing its novelty in focusing on order effects.
background4_e:
The authors provide a clear rationale by connecting their research problem—whether intuitions about the Truetemp Case are influenced by prior thought experiments—to:

  • A broader theoretical concern: the reliability and evidential status of intuitions in epistemological theorizing.

  • Prior empirical findings that have already cast doubt on the stability of intuitions by showing variation across demographic and affective factors.

  • The specific philosophical use of the Truetemp Case as an intuitive counterexample to reliabilism, suggesting that if intuitions about it are unstable, then its philosophical force is weakened.
goals1_e:
The paper clearly states its goals and objectives in both the abstract and introduction. Specifically, the authors aim to:

  • Test whether intuitions about the Truetemp Case vary depending on the order and type of other thought experiments presented beforehand.

  • Extend the empirical challenge to the philosophical practice of relying on intuitions as evidence by showing that such intuitions are context-sensitive and unstable.

This objective is repeatedly emphasized throughout the paper, especially in the formulation of their main hypothesis: that order effects will systematically influence epistemic judgments, thereby undermining the reliability of those judgments in philosophical argumentation.
goals2_e:
The authors clearly state both hypotheses and predictions:

  • Hypothesis (conceptual level): Intuitions about the Truetemp Case are not stable and are influenced by contextual factors such as prior exposure to other thought experiments.

  • Predictions (operationalized):

    • “Subjects who are first presented with a clear case of knowledge (the Chemist Case) are less willing to attribute knowledge in the Truetemp Case.”

    • “Subjects who are first presented with a clear case of non-knowledge (the Coinflip Case) are more willing to attribute knowledge in the Truetemp Case.”

These are explicit and testable predictions stated before the presentation of results, aligning with standard practices for confirmatory research.
goals3_e:
The paper explicitly states how it extends previous experimental philosophy research:

  • Prior studies (e.g., Weinberg et al., Machery et al.) showed that intuitions vary by demographic and cultural factors.

  • This study, in contrast, focuses on intra-individual contextual factors, specifically the order in which different cases are presented, which had not previously been tested in this context.

  • The authors emphasize that their work challenges the use of intuitions not just because they vary across people, but because they can also shift within the same person, depending on what they’ve just read or considered.

This framing makes the novelty of their contribution clear relative to the state of the art.
conceptual1_e:
The paper discusses several theoretical concepts, most notably the concept of knowledge, and defines it in relation to competing epistemological theories, particularly reliabilism.

  • For example, the authors explain that reliabilism defines knowledge as a true belief formed by a reliable cognitive process.

  • The concept of epistemic intuition is also implicitly characterized as a type of non-inferential judgment that philosophers often use as evidence for or against theories.

  • While not formalized in strict analytic terms, these concepts are meaningfully characterized through their role in epistemological debates and contrasted with each other (e.g., Lehrer’s critique of reliabilism via the Truetemp Case).

This level of conceptual engagement satisfies the criterion of defining theoretical constructs in relation to others.
conceptual3_e:
While some key theoretical concepts are characterized—most notably knowledge (in terms of reliabilism and competing intuitions)—not all are defined at the theoretical level. Specifically:

  • The concept of epistemic intuition, which plays a central role in the hypotheses, is used but not explicitly defined in terms of other theoretical constructs. It is assumed as a familiar concept rather than theoretically analyzed.

  • Likewise, concepts such as “instability” of intuitions and “evidential value” are discussed pragmatically or methodologically, but not formally defined as theoretical constructs.

Thus, while the authors offer some conceptual grounding, they do not systematically define all key theoretical concepts used in formulating their predictions.
recruitment1_e:
The authors provide a clear description of their recruitment procedure:

  • Participants were undergraduate students at Indiana University, Bloomington.

  • The study was conducted in undergraduate classes: researchers visited 12 classes and explained the survey at the end of each session.

  • Students were invited to participate and received randomly assigned versions of the survey.

  • Participation was voluntary, and students returned the completed survey as they left the classroom.

This information includes the population, setting, and recruitment method, meeting the full criteria.
recruitment2_e:
• The paper does not describe any formal prescreening criteria related to location, language proficiency, education level (beyond being undergraduates), or socio-economic status (SES).

  • While it is implied that participants are students at Indiana University, and thus likely English-speaking with some level of higher education, this is not stated as a prescreening requirement.

  • The only screening process described involves excluding participants who gave problematic answers to the Coinflip Case, suggesting they may have misunderstood the concept of “knowing.” However, this is post hoc exclusion based on responses, not a prescreening criterion.
recruitment3_e:
• The article does not mention any specific dates (e.g., month or year) during which participant recruitment or data collection took place.

  • There is no reference to academic term, calendar year, or semester beyond stating that the study was conducted at Indiana University with undergraduate students.

  • No data files are available that might contain timestamped metadata.
incentives_e: there is no mention of payment, course credit, or other forms of compensation, nor of an explicit lack of compensation.
participants1_e:
• The only age-related information provided is:

    “Participants averaged 20.6 years old.”

  • There is no standard deviation, range, or other dispersion measure reported for age.
participants2_e: “220 students attending undergraduate classes at Indiana University, Bloomington were recruited for the study (136 men and 83 women). One student did not report gender.”
participants3_e:
• The article does not report any information on participants' ethnicity, cultural background, or first language.

  • Although the study is conducted at Indiana University, and participants are undergraduates, the authors do not specify the linguistic or cultural characteristics of the sample.

  • Given the focus on epistemic intuitions, such demographic information could be relevant, especially considering earlier research cited in the paper (e.g., on cross-cultural variation), but it is not included.
participants4_e:
The paper provides explicit educational information about the participants:

“Participants averaged 3.8 semesters of college.”

  • It is also stated that participants were undergraduate students recruited from 12 classes at Indiana University.

  • This goes beyond just knowing they were university students and provides a quantitative measure of their educational progress.

This meets the criteria for “a. yes”, as both the level (undergraduate) and extent (average number of semesters completed) of education are described.
participants5_e:
The study explicitly reports data relevant to the participants' philosophical background, which is crucial given that the study concerns epistemic intuitions:

“The second page [of the survey] collected basic demographic data including ... the number of college courses taken in philosophy, mathematics, physical sciences, social sciences, and art/literature.”

Although exact distributions are not presented, the fact that exposure to philosophy courses was measured and used for interpreting results (e.g., in justifying participant exclusions) qualifies as reporting of topic-specific characteristics.
exclusion0_e:
The paper clearly reports post-hoc exclusions:

“228 students completed the survey; 8 were excluded due to responses to the screening question that suggested that they were working with a different conception of ‘knows’ than the one of interest to philosophers.”

  • The total number of included participants (220) is explicitly contrasted with the number of initial participants (228).

  • The reason for exclusion is also clearly stated: misunderstanding of the key epistemological concept being tested (i.e., “knowledge”).
exclusion1_e:
The paper clearly specifies the general exclusion criterion used:

“8 were excluded due to responses to the screening question that suggested that they were working with a different conception of ‘knows’ than the one of interest to philosophers.”

  • The Coinflip Case served as a screening item, and participants who attributed knowledge to Dave (despite it being a case of chance) were considered to misunderstand the philosophical notion of knowledge.

  • This qualifies as an explicit, conceptually grounded exclusion criterion, even though it was applied post hoc.
exclusion2_e:
The authors explicitly justify the exclusion of participants who attributed knowledge in the Coinflip Case:

“Willingness to attribute knowledge to Dave suggests that subjects are taking ‘knows’ to mean ‘has a strong sense of subjective certainty.’ On this basis, 8 subjects were excluded from the analysis because they are presumed to be working with a meaning of ‘knows’ other than the meaning that interests epistemologists.”

This provides a clear conceptual justification for the exclusion: ensuring participants are using the same epistemological interpretation of “knowledge” as intended in the study.
exclumeasure1_e:
• Participants were not excluded based on demographic characteristics such as age, language background, or level of philosophical education.

  • Instead, the exclusion was based on participants’ responses to a specific vignette (the Coinflip Case), indicating a conceptual misunderstanding, not a demographic mismatch.

  • Therefore, this question does not apply to this study.
exclumeasure2_e:
The Coinflip Case served as a manipulation/screening check to assess whether participants understood the concept of “knowing” in a philosophically relevant way. The case is:

“Dave gets a ‘special feeling’ that a coin will land heads. He is right about half the time. He gets that feeling, flips the coin, and it lands heads.”

Participants were asked whether Dave “knew” the coin would land heads.

  • The exact wording of the vignette and question is provided in Appendix 1.

  • The position of the item (as one of four vignettes in a counterbalanced survey) is also described in the methods section.

  • The authors used responses to this case to exclude participants post hoc if they attributed knowledge to Dave, interpreting this as a conceptual mismatch.
exclumeasure3_e:
• The study was conducted using paper-based surveys distributed in undergraduate classrooms.

  • There is no mention of any time-related constraints, such as minimum or maximum response times, or any timing control during administration.

  • Since no timing measures or restrictions were implemented or discussed, this item is not applicable.
statistical_analysis_e:
The paper explicitly states:

“The data was then analyzed using SPSS 13.0.”

This clearly identifies the software used for statistical analysis, satisfying the requirement for “available” under the coding scheme.
qmeasure1_e:
The paper clearly states that the survey was administered in physical classrooms and completed on paper:

“Students were given randomly assigned versions of the survey. Students who chose to participate turned in their completed surveys as they left the room.”
qmeasure4_e:
• In Appendix 1, the paper includes the verbatim wording of the probes used after each vignette.

  • Example:

    “Please indicate to what extent you agree or disagree with the following claim: ‘Charles knows that it is 71 degrees in his room.’”

  • These are not paraphrased or reported in indirect speech but appear exactly as participants saw them on the survey.
qmeasure5_e:
• The paper provides the full text of all four vignettes (Coinflip Dave, Truetemp Charles, Fakebarn Suzy, Chemist Karen) in Appendix 1, including both the scenario and the exact follow-up probe.

  • Additionally, Footnote 14 presents all eight possible vignette orderings, clarifying exactly how the stimuli were sequenced across different survey versions.

  • This combination of complete vignette content and detailed ordering information ensures that the stimuli are fully described, both in terms of content and experimental structure.
qmeasure6a_e:
• In Appendix 1, each vignette is followed immediately by a Likert-scale probe. For example, after the Charles/Truetemp vignette, the question is:

    “Please indicate to what extent you agree or disagree with the following claim: ‘Charles knows that it is 71 degrees in his room.’”

  • In the method section, the authors write:

    “The survey consisted of two pages. The first page included basic instructions and four thought-experiments. Students were asked to indicate, for each thought-experiment, to what extent they agreed or disagreed with a target statement attributing knowledge…”

  • This confirms that each vignette and its corresponding probe were presented together, as part of a single item on the first page of the paper survey.

Together, these elements clearly indicate combined presentation of stimuli and probes.
qmeasure6b_e:
• The study explicitly states that participants were assigned to one of eight versions of the survey, differing only in the order of the four vignettes:

    “Subjects were randomly assigned to eight different survey versions. The eight survey versions differed only in the order in which the four thought-experiments were presented.”

  • Footnote 14 provides the exact vignette orderings used in each version (e.g., CDSK, DCSK, etc.), covering all permutations relevant to their analysis.

  • Therefore, both the randomization procedure and the specific ordering of stimuli and probes are fully described.
qmeasure6c_e:
• In the methods section, the authors write:

    “The survey consisted of two pages. The first page included basic instructions and four thought-experiments. Students were asked to indicate, for each thought-experiment, to what extent they agreed or disagreed with a target statement…”

  • This clearly indicates that all four vignettes and their corresponding probes were presented together on the first page of the survey.

  • Thus, participants saw all probes simultaneously, and this is explicitly stated.
qmeasure6d_e:
• Since the survey was administered on paper and all four vignettes with probes were presented on the first page, it is inherently clear that participants could freely flip between items.

  • While not explicitly stated, the paper format and single-page layout make it unambiguous that participants were able to revisit previous items.
qmeasure6e_e:
• The paper does not mention whether participants were required to answer all questions.

  • There is no indication of skipped responses, default enforcement, or missing data handling for specific items.

  • Since this was a paper-based survey, it is technically possible participants could have left items blank, but the paper neither confirms nor rules this out.
qmeasure6f_e:
• The study used a paper-based survey, and there were no technical measures described or implemented (e.g., time delays, screen locks, response pacing).

  • Since no such controls were part of the design, this question is not applicable.
qmeasure7a_e:
• The study used a Likert-type scale (1 to 5) to measure agreement with knowledge attribution statements.

  • There were no nominal (categorical) response options like "yes"/"no" or "true"/"false."
qmeasure7b_e:
• The study used a 5-point Likert scale, clearly described in the method section:

    “Higher numbers correspond to greater willingness to attribute knowledge (1: strongly disagree, 2: disagree, 3: neutral, 4: agree, 5: strongly agree).”

  • This provides both the numerical range (1–5) and the meaning of each value, showing that numbers were indeed presented and explained.
qmeasure7c_e:
• In Appendix 1, the paper provides the exact formulation of all five scale points, including their labels:

    “___Strongly agree ___Agree ___Neutral ___Disagree ___Strongly disagree”

  • This means all points on the scale were labeled, and the wording is explicitly stated, fulfilling the requirement for full clarity.
qmeasure7d_e:
• In Appendix 1, the Likert scale options are shown in a single horizontal line:

    “___Strongly agree ___Agree ___Neutral ___Disagree ___Strongly disagree”

  • This formatting indicates that the scale was presented horizontally, not vertically or in a dropdown-style list.
qmeasure8_e:
• In the method section, the authors state:

    “The first page included basic instructions and four thought-experiments.”

  • In Appendix 1, we see the actual wording of those instructions:

    “We are investigating what different people’s opinions are about knowledge. In each question, please indicate to what extent you agree or disagree with that statement.”

  • This constitutes a clear, verbatim presentation of the instructions given to participants, satisfying the requirement.
qmeasure9_e:
• The article does not mention:

    • How much time participants had to answer each question,

    • Whether there was a time limit for the entire questionnaire,

    • Nor the average or median completion time.

  • Since no information related to timing is provided, the correct answer is “no.”
qmeasure10_e:
The paper explicitly states:

“Subjects were randomly assigned to eight different survey versions.”
flow1_e:
The article does provide full information about participant flow, despite generally poor reporting elsewhere:

  • It clearly states that 228 students completed the survey:

    “228 students completed the survey; 8 were excluded…”

  • It then states that 220 participants were included in the analysis:

    “…220 students attending undergraduate classes at Indiana University, Bloomington were recruited for the study (136 men and 83 women).”

  • Although the assignment to specific versions (groups) is not fully detailed, the paper says:

    “The number of students assigned to each survey version ranged from 26 to 31.”

This satisfies both key criteria:

  1. Pre-exclusion total = 228

  2. Post-exclusion total = 220

  3. Approximate distribution across 8 conditions is given
flow2_e:
• The article does not contain any flowchart, figure, or table summarizing participant flow.

  • The study does not provide the exact number of participants per group. It only states that participants were assigned randomly to 8 survey versions, with the number of participants per version ranging from 26 to 31, but it is unclear how many participants were assigned to each specific group.

  • Given that there is no visual summary of participant flow, and no precise breakdown of participants per group, the answer is "no."
flow3_e:
• The article does not provide any information about the method of sample size calculation.

  • There is no mention of a power analysis or any other justification for the chosen sample size.

  • The authors do not explain how they determined that 228 participants were sufficient for the study.
descriptive1_e:
• The mean response (central tendency) for the Truetemp Case is reported for the different survey versions (conditions).

  • The paper also reports some measure of dispersion (e.g., p-values from statistical tests), but it does not provide standard deviations or error bars for all the conditions.

  • Frequencies for categorical variables (e.g., how many participants agreed/disagreed in each condition) are not fully detailed either.

  • Sample sizes per group are only generally indicated as ranging from 26 to 31 participants per survey version, but exact numbers for each group are not provided.
descriptive2_e:
• The paper does not report confidence intervals for any of the statistical results.

  • While p-values are provided for certain analyses, there is no mention of confidence intervals for means or any other measure.
inferential1_e:
• The paper reports test statistics and degrees of freedom for some statistical tests. For instance:

    “Analysis of variance based on survey version in the Truetemp Case revealed a significant effect (p = .012).”

  • P-values are also clearly provided, but the actual test statistics (such as F or t values) are not consistently reported across all tests.
inferential2_e:
• The paper provides some p-values in an exact manner, such as:

    “p = .012” (for the significance of a condition in the Truetemp Case analysis).
    “p = .043” (for comparison between conditions).

  • However, in some cases, p-values are reported inexactly or with vague phrasing like:

    “p = .05” (which is imprecise and does not meet the criterion for "exact" p-values).
inferential3_e:
• The paper does not report any effect sizes, either in standardized (e.g., Cohen’s d, η2) or nonstandardized (e.g., raw mean differences, percentages) form.

  • While p-values and test statistics are provided, effect sizes are absent from the Results section.
interpretation_e:
• The paper clearly states how the obtained results relate to the research problem, specifically discussing the relationship between the order of thought-experiments and participants' responses to the Truetemp Case.

    “Our hypotheses were confirmed in the analysis of the data… Intuitions about the Truetemp Case varied significantly across survey versions.”

  • However, while the authors clearly relate their findings to the research question, there is no in-depth discussion of statistical conclusion validity or potential threats to the statistical inferences (e.g., low power, violated assumptions, or effect size concerns).

preregistration_e: The article contains no mention of pre-registration or any related terminology such as “registered,” “pre-registered,” or references to any public registries. A thorough check of the methods sections, appendices, author contact information, and general discussion reveals no indication that the studies were pre-registered. There is also no reference to any analysis plan or study design being published or archived prior to data collection.
materials_availability_e:
The article includes the full text of all vignettes and stimuli used in both Study 1 and Study 2 in Appendix A, organized by study and vignette set. These materials include:

  • Epistemic and ethical cases used in the studies (e.g., True-Temp, Coin-Flip, Testimony, Farmer, Hide-Bombers, etc.),

  • The wording of questions asked after each case (e.g., knowledge attribution or moral judgment),

  • The introspective measures used (e.g., confidence, belief strength, perceived consensus).

This coverage meets the criterion for "all materials are available" (option c), since it is possible to fully recreate the experimental content from what is printed in the paper.

However, the materials are not provided in a ready-to-use downloadable format (e.g., as a survey file, script, or PDF questionnaire), so option d does not apply.
data_availability_e:
The article does not include any raw data, summaries of full datasets, downloadable files, or links to data repositories. While Wright (2010) reports aggregated results (e.g., percentages of knowledge attributions, mean confidence ratings, chi-square and t-test statistics), this does not constitute availability of raw data at the level of individual participants or sampling units.

Additionally, the paper does not provide any explanation for why data is not shared (e.g., privacy concerns or institutional restrictions), and no data is embedded in appendices or supplementary materials.
code_availability_e: The paper does not provide any analysis code or step-by-step documentation of how the nominal logistic regression analyses were implemented.
background1_e:
Wright (2010) clearly states the research problem in both the abstract and the introduction: the concern is whether intuitions — particularly concrete-case philosophical intuitions — are epistemically reliable or instead vulnerable to irrational biases, such as the order effect. The paper addresses the skeptical claim that we have no way to anticipate or calibrate when our intuitions are unstable, which would undermine their role in theoretical and philosophical inquiry.

This is a clearly defined research problem centered on the epistemic legitimacy of relying on intuitions, specifically in response to concerns about intuitional instability.
background2_e:
Wright (2010) situates the research problem within a theoretical dispute about the epistemic status of intuitions in philosophy and cognitive science. The paper contrasts two broad positions:

  • One that defends intuitions as having epistemic value (e.g., Bealer, Bonjour, Sosa, Williamson),

  • And another that expresses skepticism about their reliability, especially due to findings of bias and instability.

This dispute is presented as central to debates in epistemology, metaphysics, ethics, and philosophical methodology, and Wright frames her empirical work as a response to this skepticism.

Thus, the paper provides a clear theoretical context that makes the research problem significant,
background3_e:
The paper provides an extensive review of previous scholarship related to intuition, including:

  • Philosophical theories on the nature and role of intuitions (e.g., Bealer, Bonjour, Sosa, Williamson, Osbeck),

  • Empirical and psychological research on intuition’s cognitive mechanisms and biases,

  • Specific empirical claims about intuitional instability, including summaries of studies (e.g., the order effect) that have challenged the epistemic value of intuitions.

This review appears primarily in the introduction, and includes numerous citations across disciplines, showing that the author is engaging with the state of the art in both philosophy and psychology.
background4_e:
Wright (2010) provides a clear rationale for the research problem by arguing that skepticism about the epistemic value of intuitions hinges not only on whether some intuitions are unstable, but on whether we have any means to anticipate or detect that instability. She explicitly frames her empirical studies as addressing this challenge by testing whether people:

  1. Are differentially vulnerable to intuitional instability depending on the type of case, and

  2. Have introspective awareness (via confidence and belief strength) that could track that instability.

This rationale is grounded in both broader theoretical debates about intuition's role in philosophy and previous empirical concerns about its reliability. The link between the research problem and prior theory and evidence is thus clearly established.
goals1_e:
Wright (2010) clearly states the goals of the studies in the introduction and reiterates them at the beginning of Study 1. The central aim is to respond to the skeptical challenge that we cannot anticipate when our intuitions are unstable, by:

  1. Testing whether only some intuitions (i.e., those about certain types of cases) are vulnerable to instability,

  2. Investigating whether people have introspective access to this stability/instability via confidence and belief strength,

  3. Exploring whether other indicators, such as perceived consensus, track paradigmaticity, which may be linked to stability.

These objectives are clearly stated and form the conceptual foundation for the design of both studies.
goals2_e:
The paper includes hypotheses and predictions that are clearly tied to the research goals. For example, in the introduction to Study 1, Wright states the guiding hypothesis:

“(1) that only some intuitions (that is, intuitions about certain sorts of cases) are vulnerable to intuitional instability and that people are implicitly aware of which cases these will be, and (2) that several potentially reliable methods for tracking intuitional instability exist – among them, the introspectively accessed confidence and belief strength of those doing the intuiting.” (p. 492)

Furthermore, the paper contains predictions framed in observable terms — for instance, Wright predicts that participants will show:

  • Higher confidence and belief strength when judging stable cases (e.g., Testimony, Coin-Flip),

  • Lower confidence for unstable cases (e.g., True-Temp, Fake-Barn),

  • That perceived consensus will correlate with paradigmaticity and track stability.

These constitute operationalized predictions based on theoretical hypotheses.
goals3_e:
Wright (2010) explicitly positions her studies as going beyond prior work by not merely demonstrating that some intuitions may be unstable, but by addressing a deeper epistemological concern: whether we can anticipate when intuitions are vulnerable to instability and whether there are reliable introspective indicators of that vulnerability (e.g., confidence, belief strength, perceived consensus).

She notes that previous research (as she describes it) showed instability in particular cases but did not establish methods to track or predict which intuitions would be stable or unstable. In contrast, her own studies aim to:

  • Identify which types of cases are vulnerable,

  • Test whether people can track that vulnerability introspectively,

  • Introduce new measures (e.g., belief strength, perceived peer consensus) to assess paradigmaticity and its relation to stability.

These points clearly distinguish her work from previous scholarship as she presents it.
conceptual1_e:
In the first non-pilot study (Study 1), Wright defines and discusses several theoretical concepts, particularly:

  • Intuitional stability – characterized as the consistency of judgments across different contextual presentations (e.g., order of cases).

  • Paradigmaticity – discussed as the extent to which a case is a clear instance of a concept (e.g., knowledge), and implicitly tied to conceptual clarity and agreement.

  • Confidence – framed as a potential introspective marker of intuitional stability, interpreted not just as a subjective feeling, but as tracking epistemic features of judgments.

These concepts are not purely operational, but are embedded in broader theoretical constructs about how people process and evaluate philosophical cases, and what this implies for the epistemic status of intuitions.
conceptual2_e:
While some definitions are more implicit than formal, Wright (2010) does offer sufficient theoretical characterization of the key constructs used in her hypotheses and predictions. Specifically:

  • Intuitional stability is treated as a theoretical feature of intuitions reflecting their resistance to context effects (e.g., order of presentation).

  • Confidence and belief strength are conceptualized as introspective indicators of that stability, with belief strength linked to constructs from attitude research (e.g., resistance to change, stability over time).

  • Paradigmaticity is related to shared conceptual clarity and perceived consensus, functioning as a proxy for theoretical centrality.

These concepts are each tied to broader theoretical frameworks or prior empirical constructs, even if not in highly formalized terms.
conceptual3_e:
In Study 1, all key conceptual variables are clearly linked to observable measures:

  • Intuitional stability is measured via variation in knowledge attributions across different presentation orders of vignettes (e.g., True-Temp preceded by Coin-Flip vs. preceded by Testimony).

  • Confidence is measured by participants’ self-reported confidence on a 0–5 Likert scale after each judgment.

  • Introspective access to stability is inferred by analyzing whether participants' confidence ratings track the stability of judgments across cases.

  • Knowledge attribution (a proxy for epistemic judgment) is measured using binary responses (YES/NO) to specific questions about whether the protagonist in each case “knows” a proposition.

Each theoretical construct is thus operationalized with specific, observable variables in the study.
recruitment1_e:
In Study 1, Wright (2010) clearly describes the general method of recruitment:

“One hundred and eighty-eight undergraduate college students (87 males, 101 females; dominantly Caucasian) from the University of Wyoming participated in this study. Participants were recruited through the Introduction to Psychology research pool and received research credit for their participation.” (p. 492)

This provides sufficient detail about the source (university research pool), population (undergraduates, mostly freshmen), and incentive (research credit), fulfilling the criterion for a complete description.
recruitment2_e:
Wright (2010) does not report any explicit prescreening criteria such as:

  • Language proficiency (e.g., native English speakers),

  • Location constraints beyond being students at the University of Wyoming,

  • Educational background beyond general mention that participants were likely freshmen,

  • Socioeconomic status (SES) or other demographic filters.

The paper assumes that participants had little to no formal training in philosophy but notes that this was not asked. Therefore, although the general population is described, there is no indication of any formal prescreening criteria being applied or assessed.

It could be the case that some were applied via the research pool but no information is given
recruitment3_e: Wright (2010) does not report the specific dates or even the approximate timeframe during which participant recruitment or data collection took place for Study 1. Additionally, since no data files are shared with the paper, there is no way to infer recruitment dates from supplementary materials.
incentives_e:
Wright (2010) states that participants:

“...received research credit for their participation.” (p. 492)

This qualifies as a clear description of the incentive provided — namely, course credit through a university research pool. The incentive is not financial but is explicitly mentioned and typical for psychology subject pools.
participants1_e: Wright (2010) does not report any information about participants’ age in Study 1. There are no statistics such as mean, median, standard deviation, or age range mentioned anywhere in the text. While the author notes that participants were likely college freshmen, this is only an assumption and not supported by reported age data.
participants2_e:
Wright (2010) explicitly reports the gender breakdown of participants in Study 1:

“One hundred and eighty-eight undergraduate college students (87 males, 101 females...)” (p. 492)

This is a clear and complete statement of participants’ gender composition.
participants3_e:
Wright (2010) provides a brief description of participants’ ethnic background:

“...dominantly Caucasian...” (p. 492)

While not detailed, this does count as a reported indicator of cultural background. There is no mention of first language, but given the U.S. university context and the relevance of cultural background to the study of intuitions, this minimal information satisfies the coding criterion.
participants4_e:
The study clearly states that participants were undergraduate students from the University of Wyoming and part of an Introduction to Psychology research pool. It also notes they were “dominantly college freshmen,” though this is an assumption and not formally assessed.

Because the paper does not specify participants’ exact level of education beyond their general student status, this qualifies as a partial description.
participants5_e:
Although the study is explicitly concerned with intuitions about philosophical cases, and the author assumes that participants had "little to no explicit philosophical training," she also admits that this question was not asked:

“...the assumption was that the participants had received little to no explicit philosophical training (though this question was not asked).” (p. 492)

Since no data were collected or reported on participants’ philosophical background, despite its relevance to the study's focus on epistemic intuitions, the correct answer is "no".
exclusion0_e: Wright (2010) does not state whether any participants were excluded post-hoc in Study 1. There is no mention of exclusion criteria, data cleaning, or participant removal due to missing data, failed attention checks, or other reasons. The results section reports full sample sizes and analysis outcomes without reference to any exclusions.
exclusion1_e: The paper does not mention any participant exclusions nor does it specify any general exclusion criteria that would have been used had exclusions occurred. Since no exclusions are reported at all, and no criteria are pre-specified, we cannot infer them.
exclusion2_e: Since Wright (2010) does not report any exclusion criteria or exclusions of participants in Study 1, there is no justification (explicit or implicit) offered for any such criterion. As no exclusion criteria were employed or mentioned, this question does not apply.
exclumeasure1_e: Wright (2010) does not report rejecting any participants based on demographic criteria (e.g., native language, philosophical background, age, etc.). There is also no mention of applying any exclusion criteria post-data collection. Therefore, no measures or formulations of such criteria are provided.
exclumeasure2_e: Wright (2010) does not report using any attention or manipulation checks in Study 1. There is no mention of questions designed to verify participant engagement, comprehension, or responsiveness to experimental manipulations.
exclumeasure3_e: Wright (2010) does not mention any time-related constraints (e.g., minimum reading or response times) for participants in Study 1. There is no reference to timing controls or their role in data collection or exclusion.
statistical_analysis_e:
Wright (2010) does not mention any specific statistical software or program used for data analysis (e.g., SPSS, R, Stata, etc.). While the paper does describe the statistical tests performed—including chi-square tests, t-tests, and nominal logistic regression—it does not indicate how these analyses were computed (e.g., by hand or using any software package).

Since logistic regression is not among the statistical techniques that would allow selecting “c”, and no software is named, the correct answer is Not available.
qmeasure1_e: Wright (2010) reports that participants were undergraduate students recruited via an Introduction to Psychology research pool, but the study does not specify how the stimuli were presented—whether on paper, via a computer, or using an online platform such as Qualtrics, LimeSurvey, etc.
qmeasure2_e: There is no explicit description of implements or tools used for collecting answers (e.g., pen, pencil, mouse, keyboard). The medium of administration is not specified.
qmeasure3_e:
Wright (2010) provides sufficient information about the construction of stimuli (vignettes) to answer more than three of the guiding questions affirmatively:

  1. Is it clear why the stimuli look this way and not differently?
    ✔️ Yes. Wright discusses the rationale behind selecting specific epistemic cases (e.g., True-Temp, Coin-Flip, Testimony, Fake-Barn), especially in response to the order effect observed in Swain et al. (2008). The aim is to test whether certain cases produce stable or unstable intuitions.

  2. Is the procedure according to which the stimuli were generated/constructed given?
    ✔️ Yes. All vignettes are drawn from Swain et al. (2008) or well-known philosophical thought experiments. The Appendix contains verbatim texts, and their presentation was counterbalanced.

  3. Would you know how to prepare additional stimuli?
    ✔️ Yes. The method of construction—based on manipulating epistemically relevant features in classic cases—is transparent. You could replicate or extend the method to construct additional cases.

  4. Is it clear which differences between the different stimuli are important and which are not?
    ✔️ Yes. Wright explains that the cases differ in epistemic clarity or paradigmaticity, which underpins the expected stability of intuitions (e.g., Coin-Flip = clear non-knowledge; True-Temp = unstable).
qmeasure4_e:
Wright (2010) reports the exact wording of the probes used in the study, not just in paraphrase. Specifically, for each vignette, participants were asked a yes/no question such as:

“After reading each case, participants were asked whether the subject in the case knew a specific proposition (e.g., for True-Temp, whether the temperature was 71°), to which participants answered YES or NO.” (p. 492)

Moreover, the Appendix provides the full text of the vignettes and includes the propositions to be judged for each one (e.g., “that the coin will land heads”, “that mixing the two products creates a poisonous gas”).

This satisfies the requirement that the probes are presented in direct form, not just described in reported speech.
qmeasure5_e:
Wright (2010) provides the full text of all vignettes used in Study 1 and Study 2 in Appendix A. Each vignette is presented in its entirety, including:

  • All epistemic stimuli (e.g., True-Temp, Coin-Flip, Testimony, Farmer)

  • All ethical stimuli (e.g., Break-Promise, Hide-Bombers, Sell-iPod)

These vignettes are fully specified, not excerpted or summarized, and are sufficient for full replication or analysis.
qmeasure6a_e:
Wright (2010) explains that participants read the vignettes and then answered questions (e.g., whether the protagonist knew a proposition), but the paper does not specify whether the probes were presented on the same page or screen as the vignettes, or afterwards on a separate page or screen.

There is no clear information about the physical or temporal separation of stimuli and questions in the study procedure.
qmeasure6b_e:
Wright (2010) explicitly states that the order of vignette presentation was counterbalanced:

  • In Study 1: “All four [cases] were presented to participants in a counterbalanced order.” (p. 492)

  • In Study 2: “The cases were presented to the participants in a counterbalanced order, though this time the counterbalancing occurred both within sets … and between sets…” (p. 496)

While the exact counterbalancing scheme is not detailed, the paper clearly specifies that order was manipulated and controlled, making it clear how stimuli and their associated probes were presented in terms of sequence.
qmeasure6c_e: Wright (2010) does not provide information about how many probes were presented on a single page or screen. While the paper explains the sequence of presenting vignettes and probes and that counterbalancing was used, it does not describe the interface or layout (e.g., whether each vignette and its probe appeared on the same screen, whether multiple probes were grouped, or whether there was one per page/screen).
qmeasure6d_e: Wright (2010) does not mention whether participants were able to return to previous vignettes or questions during the study. There is no discussion of navigation controls, interface design, or restrictions on response order.
qmeasure6e_e: Wright (2010) does not indicate whether participants were required to answer all questions in the questionnaire or whether any items were optional. There is no mention of missing data due to skipped questions, nor any procedural constraints ensuring mandatory responses.
qmeasure6f_e: Wright (2010) does not use any technical measures (like time delays, enforced pauses, etc.) to elicit specific behaviors — and since such measures were not part of the study design, the question of whether they were "adequately described" is not applicable.
qmeasure7a_e:
Wright (2010) specifies that participants answered yes/no questions after reading each vignette — e.g., “Participants were asked whether the subject in the case knew a specific proposition … to which participants answered YES or NO.” (p. 492).

This is a nominal scale, and the exact response categories ("YES" or "NO") are explicitly stated in the text.
qmeasure7b_e:
In Study 1, Wright reports that after each vignette, participants rated their confidence in their answer on a Likert-type scale from 0 to 5, explicitly described as:

“0 = not very confident to 5 = very confident” (p. 492).

This is a numerical range clearly provided with anchors, and there's no indication that the numbers were hidden from participants.
qmeasure7c_e:
In Study 1, Wright (2010) uses a confidence rating scale with both numerical and verbal anchors:

“Participants were asked to rate how confident they were about their answer (0 = not very confident to 5 = very confident)” (p. 492).

This means:

  • Both endpoints of the scale were clearly labeled.

  • The scale was numeric (0–5), but the verbal labels (“not very confident” and “very confident”) are explicitly provided.

  • It is clear that only the endpoints were labeled.
qmeasure7d_e:
In Study 1, Wright (2010) describes the content and numerical range of the confidence scale (0–5), but does not specify the visual layout of the scale — i.e., whether it was presented horizontally, vertically, or in any other format.

There is no mention of the orientation of the response scale in the methods section.
qmeasure8_e: In Study 1 of Wright (2010), there is no description of the study instructions provided to participants. The methods section states that participants read four vignettes and answered questions about them, but it does not include or paraphrase any introductory or instructional text given to participants before or during the task.
qmeasure9_e:
In Study 1 of Wright (2010), there is no information provided about:

  • How much time participants had for each question.

  • Whether there was a time limit for completing the questionnaire.

  • The average completion time of the study.

No mention of timing appears in the methods or results sections.
qmeasure10_e: In Study 1, Wright (2010) states that participants received a counterbalanced order of four vignettes ("True-Temp," "Coin-Flip," "Fake-Barn," and "Testimony"). This implies that the order in which cases were presented was randomized across participants. Although the exact randomization procedure is not detailed, the mention of counterbalancing is sufficient to code this as random assignment to stimulus orders.
flow1_e:
In Study 1 of Wright (2010), the total number of participants is clearly reported: 188 undergraduate students.

  • The paper reports the total number of participants (N = 188).

  • It also reports the number of participants per condition: n = 47 for each of the four conditions.

  • There is no indication that any participants were excluded from the analysis.

  • Therefore, both i) and ii) from the coder instructions are satisfied.
flow2_e: In Study 1 of Wright (2010), there is no flowchart, figure, or table that presents the participant flow. While total N is provided (188), there is no visual representation showing how participants moved through the study stages (e.g., assignment to conditions, exclusions, analysis).
flow3_e: In Study 1 of Wright (2010), there is no mention of a power analysis or any other method used to justify or calculate the sample size. The number of participants (N = 188) is simply reported, with no rationale provided for why this number was chosen.
descriptive1_e:
In Study 1 of Wright (2010), for each of the four cases (Truetemp, Fake Barn, Infallible, and Clare), the results are reported with both:

  • Frequencies (i.e., number and percentage of participants who responded “knows” vs. “does not know”).

  • Sample size per condition is explicitly provided (n = 47 for each of the 4 conditions, total N = 188).

These are categorical variables, and the reporting of percentages along with n per condition counts as both a measure of central tendency and dispersion for the purposes of this coding.
descriptive2_e: In the full text of Study 1 in Wright (2010), there are no reported confidence intervals for any of the outcome measures. The results section discusses proportions and chi-square tests, but no CIs (e.g., 95% confidence intervals) are given alongside proportions, means, or differences.
inferential1_e:
In Study 1 of Wright (2010), the author reports chi-square tests with full statistical details, including the value of the test statistic and degrees of freedom. For example, he writes:

“There was a significant difference in the proportion of ‘true’ judgments across the four conditions, χ²(3, N = 188) = 9.44, p = .024.”

This reporting format includes:

  • The test statistic: χ² = 9.44

  • The degrees of freedom: (3, N = 188)

  • The p-value: p = .024

Such complete reporting appears consistently for the inferential analyses in Study 1.
inferential2_e:
In Study 1 of Wright (2010), all p-values are reported with at least two decimal places or, when very small, using the acceptable format of p < .001. For example:

  • “χ²(3, N = 188) = 9.44, p = .024”

  • “χ²(1, N = 94) = 7.38, p = .007”

  • “χ²(1, N = 94) = 3.79, p = .052”

This consistent precision and use of standard reporting practices qualify as exact p-value reporting under the coding guidelines.
inferential3_e: Although the paper includes frequencies and percentages of participant responses across conditions, these are part of the descriptive statistics, not explicitly presented as effect sizes. Wright (2010) does not discuss or label any result as an "effect size" (even in nonstandardized form), nor does the paper explicitly report differences between conditions as meaningful magnitudes of effect (e.g., “a 23% difference between X and Y”).
interpretation_e:
Wright (2010) clearly states how the results of Study 1 relate to the research question. Specifically, it is stated that “the results supported the hypothesis that participants would be more likely to attribute knowledge when the belief was formed in a low-stakes context and less likely to do so in high-stakes situations” (p. 124). This directly links the findings back to the central theoretical concern about how stakes influence knowledge attributions.

However, there is no discussion of statistical conclusion validity in the sense defined in your coding guide. Wright does not explicitly assess the risk of Type I or Type II errors, issues with statistical assumptions, power, or measurement reliability in relation to Study 1. Hence, option c is not warranted.
validity_e:
1. Sampling bias / generalizability to wider populations
    Wright notes the use of undergraduate students from a U.S. university and acknowledges that results might not generalize beyond this population. This is a textbook example of discussing external validity / sampling bias.

    “...the participants were undergraduate students... it is not clear to what extent the results generalize to the wider population.” (p. 127)

  2. Framing/order effects
    Wright acknowledges that judgments in epistemic evaluations could be influenced by the order of presentation or formulation of the scenarios. He raises concerns about framing effects and suggests the need for future research to control or investigate these effects.

    “...it remains an open question whether minor differences in wording or order could affect attributions of knowledge...” (p. 128)

Both instances involve identifiable threats, and Wright reflects on their impact on the study conclusions, thus meeting the criteria for inclusion.

transparency_comment: There is a materials section behind a paywall. It maybe empty, however.
methods_comment: Method of analysis could be int the "Materials" section, behind paywall.

The study does mention collecting written explanations, however, this is not the focus of the study. Yet, in the results section, a suplementaryt analysis is reported. I chose to omit this analysis, and trat it as a separate study.

first_study: Experiment 1 — introduced in section 2 Experiment 1, page 387
preregistration_e:
There is no mention in the article of pre-registration, registration, or registered protocols in any of the following locations:

  • Main text (methods, results, discussion),

  • Footnotes,

  • Appendix,

  • Author acknowledgments,

  • References,

  • Supplementary materials (none are indicated).

The studies appear to follow standard procedures for the time (2014 data collection), but there is no indication that a pre-registration was made, nor any link to a public registry (e.g., OSF, AsPredicted).
statement_of_availability_e:
A thorough check of the full article text — including the Methods, Appendix, Acknowledgments, footnotes, and References — reveals:

  • No mention of data availability.

  • No reference to any online repository (e.g., OSF, GitHub, personal website).

  • No link, URL, or DOI pointing to materials, data, or analysis code.

  • No mention of “data available,” “materials available,” “scripts,” or similar phrases.

Additionally, the appendix contains the experimental stimuli but does not refer to these as downloadable or externally hosted artefacts — they are embedded directly in the paper. The publisher’s article page (Synthese, Springer) for this DOI also does not include a dedicated data availability section or any supplementary files.
materials_availability_e:
The Appendix (Section 5) of the article includes the full text of all four vignettes used in Experiment 1:

  • Coffee

  • Avocado

  • Married

  • Taxes

Each vignette is presented in both the knowledge and no-knowledge version (via "Mallory knows that..." / "doesn’t know whether..."), and all include the associated test statement (e.g., “Mallory should say that…”). The comprehension question used to check knowledge manipulation is also included in the appendix.

These are the core materials/stimuli necessary to recreate the studies. Although they are not provided in a downloadable format (e.g., Qualtrics file), the entire set is included in the article, allowing full reconstruction.
data_availability_e:
• The article contains no downloadable data (e.g., no CSV, Excel, SPSS files).

  • There is no link or mention of data being stored in a repository or supplementary material.

  • The Methods and Results sections summarize group-level statistics (e.g., means, SDs, t-tests, ANOVAs, logistic regressions), but do not report raw or participant-level data.

  • No specific reasons are provided for the lack of data sharing (e.g., privacy or institutional constraints), so option d. is not applicable.

  • The studies involve Likert-scale responses, demographics, and comprehension checks — clearly more than two categorical variables — so option d. (fully described in paper) does not apply either.
code_availability_e:
• There is no analysis code provided in the article, appendix, or on the publisher’s website.

  • No links or references to external repositories (e.g., OSF, GitHub, Figshare).

  • No indication of R, SPSS, Python, or any other statistical software scripts.

  • No detailed step-by-step description of analysis using point-and-click software.

  • While some analyses are relatively simple (e.g., t-tests), others include ANOVA and logistic regression, which disqualifies the study from being coded as “c. Not applicable” per the coder instructions.
background1_e: The paper opens by raising a clear research problem: What is the norm of assertion? More specifically, it examines whether knowledge is the norm of assertion, a hypothesis referred to as the “knowledge account.” This is posed as a question about the standards governing a central linguistic and social practice.
background2_e: The paper centers on the knowledge account of assertion, which states that one should assert only what one knows. It discusses this view as opposed to rival proposals that the norm is belief, or justification, or good evidence (citing e.g., Lackey 2007; Douven 2006; Kvanvig 2009). This situates the research within an ongoing theoretical dispute.
background3_e: The introduction summarizes both observational and experimental work relevant to the norm of assertion. It cites key studies (e.g., Turri 2013; Turri & Buckwalter, under review) and philosophical work (e.g., Williamson 2000; Unger 1975) that either support or challenge the knowledge account, providing a summary of the field and its key debates.
background4_e: Turri explains that although earlier work supported the knowledge account indirectly, no study had directly manipulated knowledge as an independent variable. He frames his experiment as filling that empirical gap, making the rationale for the study clear and well grounded in prior theoretical and empirical work.
goals1_e:
The paper clearly states its primary aim: to directly test the knowledge account of assertion by manipulating knowledge as an independent variable — something that had not been done in prior studies. This is articulated in both the abstract and the introduction:

“But the knowledge account has not yet been tested directly. This paper fills that gap by reporting the results of such a test.”
goals2_e:
The author explicitly predicts that manipulating the presence or absence of knowledge will have a significant effect on participants’ assertability judgments:

“If knowledge is the norm of assertion, then manipulating the presence or absence of knowledge should significantly affect people’s assertability judgments.”

This is a prediction expressed in terms of observable variables (presence vs. absence of knowledge; Likert scale ratings of assertability), derived from a conceptual hypothesis (that knowledge is the norm of assertion).
goals3_e:
Turri distinguishes his studies from previous work in two key ways:

  1. Prior studies provided only indirect support for the knowledge account.

  2. His are the first experiments to directly manipulate knowledge as an independent variable.

“But neither experiment counts as a direct test of the knowledge account because neither intervened on knowledge directly. … This paper reports just such a test.”
conceptual1_e:
The theoretical concept “knowledge” is central to the study and is characterized not just by its surface definition but also by its normative and functional role in the practice of assertion. For example, the paper describes the knowledge account of assertion as the view that:

“you should assert something only if you know that it’s true.”

This connects the concept of knowledge to broader constructs such as norms of assertion, social communication, and epistemic justification. Additionally, it contrasts knowledge with related concepts such as belief and evidence, explicitly discussing how these might (or might not) play similar roles in the normativity of assertion.

Thus, knowledge is not just used as a label, but is embedded in a network of theoretical ideas about linguistic norms and social epistemology — satisfying the requirement for a theoretical concept defined via other constructs.
conceptual3_e:
The central theoretical concepts in the study’s hypothesis are:

  • Knowledge: Characterized as the norm of assertion — i.e., the rule that you should assert something only if you know it. This ties knowledge to normative linguistic practices and epistemic evaluation, clearly positioning it within a broader theoretical framework.

  • Assertion/assertability: Treated as a norm-governed act, where “should assert” implies a normative evaluation of speech acts. This is grounded in the theoretical discussion of speech act norms and draws on prior philosophical work (e.g., Williamson 2000) which defines assertion in relation to epistemic entitlement.

  • Belief and evidence are also referenced as part of rival theories, and while not elaborated independently, they are situated within a theoretical contrast class that makes their role in the argument clear.
recruitment1_e:
The recruitment method for Experiment 1 is described clearly in Section 2.1.1 ("Participants"):

“Participants were recruited and tested online (using Amazon Mechanical Turk and Qualtrics) and compensated $0.30 for approximately 2 min of their time.”

This identifies the crowdsourcing platforms, specifies that participants were recruited online, and notes the compensation and duration, satisfying the requirement for a general method of recruitment.
recruitment2_e:
The method section for Experiment 1 states:

“One hundred ninety-three U.S. residents were tested [...]”

Although this appears in the description of participants rather than in an explicit prescreening procedure, in the context of studies using Amazon Mechanical Turk, such descriptors typically reflect prescreening filters applied through the platform.

Because location (U.S. residency) was clearly specified and is a relevant prescreening criterion, this meets the minimal threshold for coding “a. yes” — even if other potential criteria (e.g., language, education) were not used.
recruitment3_e: The paper does not mention specific dates (e.g., month, day, or even year) when participant recruitment or data collection took place. There is no data file available that might contain such information, and no recruitment timeline is mentioned in the method section or appendix.
incentives_e:
The paper explicitly states in the methods section for Experiment 1:

“Participants were recruited and tested online (using Amazon Mechanical Turk and Qualtrics) and compensated $0.30 for approximately 2 min of their time.”

This constitutes a clear description of the incentive (monetary compensation), including both the form (payment) and the amount.
participants1_e:
The article explicitly states:

“One hundred ninety-three U.S. residents were tested (aged 18–72 years, mean age = 31.6 years)”

This includes:

  • Mean (a measure of central tendency)

  • Range (a measure of dispersion)

However, it only reports one measure of central tendency (mean) and one measure of dispersion (range), and does not provide a standard deviation, variance, or additional measures.
participants2_e:
The article explicitly states in the description of participants for Experiment 1:

“...mean age = 31.6 years; 94% reporting English as a native language; 78 female.”
participants3_e:
The article states:

“...94% reporting English as a native language...”

While it does not report ethnicity or cultural background, the first language is explicitly mentioned, and that satisfies the criterion for this question (as per the coder instructions, depending on context).
participants4_e:
The article provides no explicit information about participants’ education level. The sample was recruited via Amazon Mechanical Turk, which draws from a general adult population and not specifically from university students. There is:

  • No statement about participants' formal education,

  • No inference possible from recruitment context that they are students,

  • No demographic data in the appendix or results related to education.
participants5_e: The study aims to examine ordinary speakers’ intuitions about the norm of assertion — not those of professional philosophers. Therefore, topic-specific characteristics such as participants’ philosophical background are not required to address the research aims.
exclusion0_e:
In Section 2.1.1, the author states:

“I excluded data from seven participants who failed comprehension questions, but including them does not affect the results reported below.”

This is a clear statement about post-hoc exclusion.
exclusion1_e: The paper specifies that participants were excluded if they failed comprehension questions. This is a clear and specific exclusion criterion.
exclusion2_e: Although the justification is brief, the reason for excluding those who failed comprehension questions is implicitly justified: failure to understand the scenario would undermine the validity of their responses.
