Moreover, the author assures that “including them does not affect the results,” suggesting the exclusion was made for data quality reasons, which is a standard justification.
exclumeasure1_e:
The only exclusion reported in the study concerns participants who failed comprehension questions — not those who failed to meet demographic criteria such as native language, education, or nationality.

There is no indication that demographic criteria (e.g., non-native speakers or philosophical background) were used to exclude anyone after data collection, so the question of whether such criteria were presented is not applicable.
exclumeasure2_e:
The paper clearly states that a comprehension question was used to check whether participants understood the key manipulation (knowledge vs. no knowledge). In Section 2.1.2, Turri writes:

“After responding to the test statement, participants proceeded to a new screen and answered from memory a comprehension question about whether Mallory knew the relevant information.”

In the Appendix, the exact formulation of this check is provided:

Comprehension question: “Mallory _____ know the relevant information. (does / does not)”

This satisfies the requirement for an explicit description of the manipulation check, including question wording and placement in the procedure.
exclumeasure3_e:
There is no indication anywhere in the paper that time-related constraints (such as a minimum time for reading or responding) were used in the study. The methods section mentions that the study took approximately 2 minutes, but this is descriptive, not a constraint.

Since no time constraints were applied or mentioned, this item is not applicable.
statistical_analysis_e:
The paper does not mention any specific statistical software (e.g., SPSS, R, Stata, Python) used to perform the analyses. The results section includes:

  • ANOVA

  • Independent-samples t-tests

  • Logistic regression

However, no program is named, and there is no description of how the computations were performed (e.g., by hand or using software).

Also, because the study uses ANOVA and logistic regression, it does not qualify for “c. Not applicable”.
qmeasure1_e:
In Section 2.1.1 ("Participants"), the paper states:

“Participants were recruited and tested online (using Amazon Mechanical Turk and Qualtrics)…”

This provides a clear description of the platform used for data collection (MTurk) and the survey software used to present the stimuli and collect responses (Qualtrics).
qmeasure2_e: The study was conducted entirely online using Amazon Mechanical Turk and Qualtrics, as explicitly stated in the methods section.
qmeasure3_e:
While the paper does not include an extended methodological appendix explaining how the stimuli were designed from scratch, the following points satisfy the coder instructions:

  • The Appendix includes the full text of all vignettes used in the study (coffee, avocado, married, taxes), with both knowledge and no-knowledge conditions.

  • The difference between conditions is always the presence or absence of the phrase “Mallory knows that...” vs. “Mallory doesn’t know whether...”, clearly indicating the manipulated variable.

  • The stimuli are short, controlled, and uniform in structure, making it easy to infer how additional similar stimuli could be created.

  • The purpose of the manipulation is explained in the introduction and methods: to directly test the role of knowledge in normative judgments about assertion.

This allows a coder to confidently answer at least three of the guiding questions affirmatively.
qmeasure4_e:
The Appendix of the article provides the exact wording of the key probe used in the study:

Test statement: “Mallory should say that [the proposition] is true.”

This is not reported speech or paraphrased; it is the verbatim formulation presented to participants. Additionally, the comprehension check is also included in full:

Comprehension question: “Mallory _____ know the relevant information. (does / does not)”
qmeasure5_e:
The Appendix includes the full text of all four vignettes used in the experiment:

  • Coffee

  • Avocado

  • Married

  • Taxes

Each vignette is presented with both versions of the manipulated condition (i.e., “Mallory knows that...” vs. “Mallory doesn’t know whether...”), followed by the test statement. This means:

  • All stimuli used in the study are fully disclosed.

  • No only-partial examples or vague summaries are provided.

  • The reader could reconstruct the full set of materials from the paper itself.
qmeasure6a_e:
In Section 2.1.2, the procedure is described as follows:

“Each participant read a single story about an agent, Mallory, who is asked a question. … After the vignette, participants rated their agreement with the key test statement: Mallory ‘should say’ that the relevant proposition is true. Responses were collected on a standard 6-point Likert scale…”

This indicates that the vignette and probe were presented sequentially, not on the same screen or page. The phrase “after the vignette” clearly signals that the stimulus and probe were presented separately.
qmeasure6b_e:
In Section 2.1.2, the procedure is described as follows:

“Each participant read a single story about an agent, Mallory, who is asked a question. … After the vignette, participants rated their agreement with the key test statement: Mallory ‘should say’ that the relevant proposition is true. Responses were collected on a standard 6-point Likert scale…”

This indicates that the vignette and probe were presented sequentially, not on the same screen or page. The phrase “after the vignette” clearly signals that the stimulus and probe were presented separately.
qmeasure6c_e:
Each participant was assigned to one of eight conditions in a 2 (knowledge vs. no-knowledge) × 4 (vignette) between-subjects design. As such:

  • Each participant read only one vignette and responded to one corresponding probe.

  • There was no sequence of multiple stimuli or probes to be randomized or ordered.

Because the design involves a single vignette-probe pair per participant, the issue of order or randomization of multiple probes does not apply.
qmeasure6d_e: Since participants only viewed a single vignette-probe pair, the issue of navigating back to previous stimuli or questions does not arise. The question assumes a multi-item setup, which is not the case here.
qmeasure6e_e: The article does not state whether any of the questionnaire items — including the assertability probe, the comprehension check, or demographic questions — were mandatory. There is no mention of required responses, enforced completion, or missing data due to unanswered items.
qmeasure6f_e:
There is no indication in the article that any technical measures were used to control participant behavior — such as time delays between questions, forced response timing, or screen-lock features.

Because no such measures were employed, the question of whether they were adequately described is not applicable.
qmeasure7a_e:
A nominal scale was used for the comprehension question, which appears in both the method section and the appendix:

“Mallory _____ know the relevant information. (does / does not)”

This is a binary nominal response format, and the exact answer categories (“does” / “does not”) are clearly and explicitly provided.
qmeasure7b_e:
In Section 2.1.2, the paper states:

“Responses were collected on a standard 6-point Likert scale, 1 (‘strongly disagree’)–6 (‘strongly agree’).”

This provides a clear numerical range (1 to 6) and identifies the scale anchors, confirming that numbers were presented to participants.
qmeasure7c_e:
The paper specifies:

“Responses were collected on a standard 6-point Likert scale, 1 (‘strongly disagree’)–6 (‘strongly agree’).”

This clearly indicates that only the endpoints (anchors) were labeled and provides their exact formulations. Even though the intermediate points are not described, the coder instruction allows for “yes” if it is clear how many points were labeled — which, in this case, is just the endpoints.
qmeasure7d_e: The article does not specify the visual layout of the Likert scale — whether it was presented horizontally, vertically, or in any other format. There is no mention of scale orientation in the methods section, appendix, or elsewhere.
qmeasure8_e:
The article does not include the exact wording or even a summary description of the instructions provided to participants before or during the study. There is:

  • No mention of how the study was introduced,

  • No motivational framing,

  • No instruction-related content in the methods section, appendix, or elsewhere.
qmeasure9_e:
In Section 2.1.1, the paper states:

“Participants were recruited and tested online (using Amazon Mechanical Turk and Qualtrics) and compensated $0.30 for approximately 2 min of their time.”
qmeasure10_e:
In Section 2.1.2, the paper states:

“Participants were randomly assigned to one of eight conditions in a 2 (Knows: knowledge/no-knowledge) × 4 (Vignette: coffee/avocado/married/taxes) between-subjects design.”
flow1_e:
The paper provides the following:

  • Total number of participants tested:

    “One hundred ninety-three U.S. residents were tested…”

  • Number excluded:

    “I excluded data from seven participants who failed comprehension questions…”

  • Final number analyzed: can be inferred as 193 – 7 = 186, and this aligns with degrees of freedom in the ANOVA:

    “F(1, 161) = 515.79” and “t(191) = 26.52” (note the latter uses full sample, suggesting mixed reporting)

However, group-level assignment details post-exclusion are not provided (e.g., number of participants in the knowledge vs. no-knowledge conditions after exclusions). While we know there were 8 between-subjects groups (2 × 4), the number of analyzed participants per condition is not specified, nor is a flowchart or detailed breakdown provided.
flow2_e:
The article does not include any flowchart, figure, or table that visually or systematically presents:

  • Total participants,

  • Exclusions,

  • Group assignments (pre- or post-exclusion),

  • Final numbers included in analyses.

All relevant participant flow information is embedded in the text only and not presented in any visual or tabular format.
flow3_e:
The article provides no justification or explanation of how the sample size (N = 193) was determined. There is:

  • No mention of power analysis,

  • No discussion of expected effect size,

  • No reference to prior studies to guide sample size planning,

  • No mention of resource constraints or target Ns.
descriptive1_e:
The paper reports descriptive statistics for the main dependent variable (agreement with the test statement) at the condition level:

  • Mean and standard deviation are provided for the knowledge condition and no-knowledge condition:

    “M = 5.35, SD = 1.06” (knowledge)
    “M = 1.70, SD = 0.84” (no-knowledge)

  • A figure shows the percentage of participants agreeing in each condition (Fig. 1, left panel), which gives categorical frequencies.

However:

  • The study includes 8 cells (2 knowledge levels × 4 vignettes), but per-cell descriptive statistics (means, SDs, frequencies) are not provided.

  • Per-condition sample sizes are also not reported.

  • Demographics (e.g., gender, native language) are described in aggregate, not by condition.

Thus, while some central tendency and dispersion measures are given, they are not complete for all experimental cells
descriptive2_e:
The paper reports one confidence interval in the Results section of Experiment 1:

“MD = 3.64, 95% CI for MD = 3.37 to 3.91”

This is a confidence interval for the mean difference between conditions, not for the condition means themselves. There are:

  • No confidence intervals for condition-level means,

  • No confidence intervals for categorical frequencies (e.g., proportions agreeing),

  • No confidence intervals for other experiments’ descriptive statistics.
inferential1_e:
The paper reports all test statistics used in Experiment 1, including:

  • ANOVA:

    “F(1, 161) = 515.79, p < 0.001”

  • Independent samples t-test:

    “t(191) = 26.52, p < 0.001, MD = 3.64, 95% CI for MD = 3.37 to 3.91”

  • Binary logistic regression:

    “χ²(1, N = 193) = 189.12, p < 0.001”

These examples include:

  • The test statistic (F, t, χ²),

  • The degrees of freedom,

  • And the p-values.
inferential2_e:
In the results section of Experiment 1, we find both exact and inexact p-values:

  • Exact p-values:

    • None are reported as exact numeric values like p = 0.032 or p = 0.045.

  • Inexact p-values:

    • All are reported in the form p < 0.001 (e.g., in ANOVA, t-test, logistic regression).

While p < 0.001 is acceptable for very small p-values, there are no other p-values in the article reported to two or more decimal places — not even when the effect is less extreme. This means the paper relies entirely on inexact reporting.

However, since p < 0.001 is accepted as precise enough for very small p-values, and those are the only p-values reported, we can charitably code this as b — but not c, since there are no p-values reported exactly to two decimal places.
inferential3_e:
The paper reports nonstandardized effect sizes, such as:

  • Mean difference between conditions:

    “MD = 3.64, 95% CI for MD = 3.37 to 3.91”

  • Percent agreement in each condition:

    “In the knowledge condition, 94% of participants agreed… compared to 4% in the no-knowledge condition.”

  • Odds ratio from logistic regression:

    “...the odds of agreeing that she should make the assertion increased by a factor of nearly 350... 95% CI for odds ratio = 95–1276.”

However, the paper does not report standardized effect sizes such as Cohen’s d, η², or Cramer’s V, with the sole exception of:

  • Cohen’s d = 3.84 for the t-test comparison in Experiment 1.
interpretation_e:
• Clear statement of how the results relate to the hypothesis:
    After Study 1, the author explicitly states:

    “The results are exactly as the knowledge account would predict and, thus, strongly support the knowledge account.”
    This confirms that the findings are interpreted as supporting the hypothesis that knowledge is the norm of assertion.

  • Discussion of statistical conclusion validity:
    The author raises and evaluates the possibility that the manipulation may not have isolated knowledge:

    “...participants in the no-knowledge conditions denied assertability because they inferred that belief or evidence was lacking, rather than knowledge.”
    He argues this is unlikely based on prior research and motivates further studies (Experiments 2 and 3) to rule out this alternative explanation. This constitutes:

    • Raising a possible threat to the validity of the causal/statistical conclusion, and

    • Assessing its seriousness and testing it in follow-up studies.
validity_e:
• Threat to generalizability – Sampling bias:
    In the final paragraph of the general discussion, the author acknowledges:

    “Although our results suggest that neither gender nor age significantly affect judgments of assertability or its relationship to knowledge, further work could investigate whether there are interesting cross-cultural or developmental differences in judgments of assertability.”
    This explicitly raises the issue of generalizability to other populations (cross-cultural and developmental), indicating awareness of potential sampling limitations.

  • Threat to construct validity – Construct confounding (belief/evidence confound):
    In the discussion of Experiment 1, Turri anticipates a possible confound:

    “...participants in the no-knowledge conditions denied assertability because they inferred that belief or evidence was lacking, rather than knowledge.”
    He raises and evaluates whether participants were responding to something other than knowledge, which is a construct validity threat (i.e., operationalization may have included unintended constructs like belief or evidence).

preregistration_e: There is no mention anywhere in the main text, author note, methods sections, results sections, or supplementary materials of the study being pre-registered. The authors do not use terms like pre-registration, registered, or refer to any pre-registration platform such as OSF, AsPredicted, or clinicaltrials.gov. The supplementary materials contain full vignettes but no pre-registration plan, design document, or time-stamped protocol. Thus, based on the available information, the study does not appear to have been pre-registered.
statement_of_availability_e:
The main article includes a direct statement about the availability of all materials, data, and analysis scripts. In the Method section of Study 1, the authors state:

“The full vignettes and all other study materials are available at https://github.com/phillipsjs/trueHappiness.”

Later, they also write:

“The statistical code for running both sets of analyses is provided (along with the data and stimuli) at https://github.com/phillipsjs/trueHappiness.”

This repository includes:

  • Materials: Full vignettes for all conditions (confirmed in the supplementary text you provided),

  • Data: Raw data for the studies,

  • Analysis code: Scripts used for statistical analysis.
materials_availability_e:
The article explicitly states that:

“The full vignettes and all other study materials are available at https://github.com/phillipsjs/trueHappiness.”

Upon inspection of this repository (as indicated in both the article and the supplementary materials), the following holds:

  • All stimuli (the written vignettes) for Study 1 are fully available. You've also confirmed this by providing them here.

  • These materials are provided in their final, ready-to-use form, exactly as they were used in the study (i.e., with clear condition assignment: morally good vs. morally bad; precise wording; structured per agent).

  • There is no indication that anything was modified, redacted, or partially withheld.
data_availability_e:
https://github.com/phillipsjs/trueHappiness/tree/master/Data/Study_1

 

The article states explicitly:

“The statistical code for running both sets of analyses is provided (along with the data and stimuli) at https://github.com/phillipsjs/trueHappiness.”

This GitHub repository contains raw data files corresponding to each of the five studies. These are downloadable in standard formats (e.g., CSV), include participant-level data, and are sufficient to replicate the analyses reported in the paper.

There is no indication that any subset of the data is missing or withheld, and there are no stated restrictions or exclusions based on privacy or other constraints.
code_availability_e:
https://github.com/phillipsjs/trueHappiness/blob/master/Happiness_Analysis_Script.R

 

The article states:

“The statistical code for running both sets of analyses is provided (along with the data and stimuli) at https://github.com/phillipsjs/trueHappiness.”

This confirms that analysis code is available. The repository includes R scripts using the lme4 package for linear mixed-effects models, which go beyond basic statistical operations like t-tests or descriptive statistics (e.g., they include multilevel modeling and likelihood-ratio tests). Therefore, option d does not apply.
background1_e:
The paper clearly formulates a research problem: whether the ordinary concept of happiness is purely descriptive (focused only on psychological states) or whether it includes an evaluative (moral) component. This is introduced explicitly in the abstract and reiterated in the Introduction:

“The key question is whether (a) people’s ordinary concept is purely descriptive or (b) people’s ordinary concept actually involves an evaluative component.”
background2_e:
The paper presents a theoretical dispute between the descriptive psychological model of happiness (common in psychology) and the evaluative concept of happiness (defended by philosophers such as Aristotle and Foot). The authors contrast these views to frame the significance of their inquiry:

“Within psychology, research on happiness has converged on a conception of happiness that is straightforwardly descriptive… In contrast… philosophers have long argued that… happiness is not only a matter of feeling good, but also a matter of being good.”
background3_e: The article cites numerous prior studies on both descriptive and evaluative theories of happiness, including empirical findings (e.g., Phillips et al., 2011; King & Napa, 1998) and philosophical positions (e.g., Aristotle, Foot, Kraut). It also references relevant literature on related folk concepts influenced by morality (e.g., intentional action, knowledge).
background4_e:
The authors explicitly link their research question to a gap between scientific conceptions of happiness (which are descriptive) and folk intuitions, which may be morally evaluative. They explain the importance of understanding how ordinary people think about happiness and contrast it with existing scientific definitions:

“The present investigation aims to decide between these three hypotheses…”
“The studies reported here draw on these theoretical frameworks to explore questions about people’s ordinary folk concept of happiness.”

This provides a strong rationale grounded in both theoretical debate and empirical gaps.
goals1_e:
The article clearly articulates its aim both in the abstract and the introduction. The authors state that the goal of the research is to test whether the ordinary concept of happiness is purely descriptive or involves an evaluative (moral) component:

“Five studies systematically investigate and explain the impact of morality on ordinary assessments of happiness.”

“The present investigation aims to decide between these three hypotheses…”

The three hypotheses (bias/performance error, descriptive mediation, and evaluative concept) are explicitly framed in the introduction, and each study is designed to distinguish between them. This constitutes a clear and theory-driven articulation of the studies’ objectives.
goals2_e:
The authors explicitly frame their studies around competing hypotheses about the nature of the folk concept of happiness (e.g., performance error vs. evaluative concept). They also formulate specific predictions for each study based on these hypotheses. For instance:

  • In Study 2:

“If the effect in the previous study arose from a motivational bias, then we would expect this effect to decrease when participants are given evidence that happiness is not actually such a desirable or good thing.”

  • In Study 3:

“The key question was whether participants would be more reluctant to attribute happiness to the evil agent than to the agent whose life was just slightly morally bad.”

  • In Study 5:

“The key question is whether these effects will be differentially reduced when explicit information about the agents’ psychological states is provided.”

These are all predictions formulated in observable terms (e.g. comparison of happiness ratings under different moral conditions), grounded in conceptual hypotheses about the structure of the happiness concept.
goals3_e:
Justification:
The paper explicitly discusses how it builds on and extends prior research, particularly that of Phillips et al. (2011) and King & Napa (1998). It notes that earlier studies showed a relationship between morality and happiness judgments but had limitations (e.g., between-subjects designs, untrained participants, single vignettes). For example:

“Previous research… asked completely untrained participants to make assessments… based on only a single brief vignette. Accordingly, one may worry that these results… arose from a misunderstanding of the task…” (Study 1)

“The present investigation aims to decide between these three hypotheses…”

Moreover, the paper distinguishes its contribution by:

  • Testing trained experts alongside laypeople (Study 1),

  • Using within-subjects designs (Study 1),

  • Ruling out motivational bias (Studies 2 & 3),

  • Disentangling perceived affect from happiness judgments (Studies 4a & 4b),

  • Comparing moral vs. nonmoral influences (Study 5).

These design and theoretical refinements show clearly how the present research differs from and improves upon prior work.
conceptual1_e:
In the introduction, the authors define the concept of happiness using two competing theoretical characterizations:

  • Descriptive concept: defined in terms of psychological constructs such as high positive affect, low negative affect, and high life satisfaction.

  • Evaluative concept: defined in part by moral or normative value — the idea that “happiness is not only a matter of feeling good, but also a matter of being good.”

These definitions situate happiness within broader theoretical frameworks involving constructs like positive/negative affect, life satisfaction, moral value, performance error, and conceptual structure (e.g., dual character concepts). Therefore, at least one key theoretical concept (happiness) is explicitly characterized in terms of other constructs, satisfying the criterion for yes.
conceptual2_e:
All key theoretical concepts used in the hypotheses and predictions are sufficiently characterized within the theoretical framework laid out in the paper — either directly or through contrast with alternative views. Specifically:

  • Happiness is defined both in descriptive terms (positive affect, low negative affect, life satisfaction) and in evaluative terms (a life being morally good or bad).

  • Moral value is operationalized through examples (e.g., caring for children vs. harming them) and is treated as a dimension along which lives can vary; it is implicitly tied to normative assessments of right and wrong.

  • Performance error and motivational bias are described in the context of known psychological phenomena (e.g., “desire to believe in a just world,” “misapplication of one’s own concept”) and are thus characterized in relation to broader theoretical constructs from cognitive and social psychology.

Even though not every construct receives a formal definition, each is clearly embedded in a network of related theoretical ideas sufficient to support the hypotheses and predictions. Therefore, “yes” is justified.
conceptual3_e:
In Study 1, all key conceptual variables are explicitly linked to observable measures:

  • Happiness (the main dependent variable) is operationalized through a 7-point Likert scale response to the statement:

    “[Agent] is happy.”

  • Descriptive psychological states (used in comprehension checks) are linked to three true/false statements assessing whether participants understood the agent to be experiencing high positive affect, low negative affect, and high life satisfaction.

  • Moral value (the main independent variable) is manipulated via written vignettes, where agents perform morally good or morally bad actions (e.g., helping vs. harming children, reading to vs. abusing a niece). These manipulations were pretested for moral valence, and the text notes:

    “...the only difference between them was a moral difference.”

  • Expertise is measured using a self-report scale with items such as:

    “To what degree do you identify yourself as a happiness/positive psychology researcher?” (1–7 scale)

All theoretical constructs in the study are thus clearly connected to specific, observable measurement instruments.
recruitment1_e:
Justification:
The recruitment methods for all participant groups in Study 1 are clearly described:

  • Nonresearchers were recruited via Amazon’s Mechanical Turk, a widely recognized crowdsourcing platform:

    “...were recruited from the United States using Amazon’s Mechanical Turk (Buhrmester, Kwang, & Gosling, 2011...)”

  • Researchers and Experts were recruited through academic psychology listservs, which are specified:

    “...recruited through academic psychology listervs (e.g., International Society for Research in Emotion, Judgment and Decision Making, Society for Affective Neuroscience, Society for Philosophy and Psychology, Society for Affective Science, Society for Psychophysiological Research, Society for Research in Child Development, and Society for Research in Psychopathology).”
recruitment2_e:
While the authors report demographic information (age, gender, education, SES) after data collection and describe the source of participants (e.g., MTurk, academic listservs), they do not specify any prescreening criteria used to select or exclude participants before recruitment.

There is:

  • No mention of filtering based on location (though U.S.-based MTurk samples are implied),

  • No statement of prescreening for language proficiency, education level, or SES,

  • No indication that such factors were used to qualify participants before data collection began.

Therefore, although post hoc demographic characteristics are reported, prescreening criteria are not described, which warrants no.
recruitment3_e: The article does not contain any explicit mention of the dates (e.g., month or year) when participant recruitment or data collection occurred. Additionally, the data set available on GitHub does not include any variables indicating the date of participation (e.g., no column labeled date, completion_date, etc.). Thus, the specific timing of recruitment cannot be determined from either the article or the accompanying data.
incentives_e: The article explicitly states that participants were recruited through Amazon Mechanical Turk (MTurk). Since MTurk is a paid crowdsourcing platform, this implies participants received financial compensation, even if no exact amount is mentioned.
participants1_e:
In the Results section for Study 1, the authors report:

  • Mean age: 36.25 years

  • Median age: 33 years

  • Standard deviation: 11.56

  • Range: 18–74
participants2_e:
In the Results section for Study 1, the authors report gender distribution:
“Of these participants, 306 were female and 294 were male.”
participants3_e:
In the Results section for Study 1, the authors report gender distribution:
“Of these participants, 306 were female and 294 were male.”
participants4_e: the dataset does include information on education
participants5_e: In datasetst, he study does provide information about topic-specific characteristics, particularly relevant if the goal was to assess expert intuitions.
exclusion0_e:
The paper clearly states in the Participants subsection of Study 1 (p. 942) that:

"We initially collected 302 responses, but excluded 18 participants who failed an instructional manipulation check or left the study early."
exclusion1_e:
The paper specifies general exclusion criteria as follows:

"We initially collected 302 responses, but excluded 18 participants who failed an instructional manipulation check or left the study early."

This sentence clearly defines the criteria used for exclusion: failing an instructional manipulation check or not completing the study.
exclusion2_e: The exclusion of participants is justified implicitly by the nature of the criteria: failing an instructional manipulation check or leaving the study early. These are standard quality-control measures in psychological research, implying that data from such participants may not be reliable or complete enough for inclusion in the analysis.
exclumeasure1_e: The exclusions described in the paper and confirmed by the dataset were based on failing an instructional manipulation check or leaving the study early, not on demographic criteria such as nativeness or philosophical education. Therefore, no demographic exclusion criteria were used or needed to be measured.
exclumeasure2_e:
In the "Measures" subsection of Study 1 (p. 1256), under the heading Comprehension check, the authors write:

Comprehension check. “To ensure that participants had understood the vignette, we asked them a simple factual question: ‘Did this person do something morally good or morally bad?’ Participants who failed to answer this question correctly were excluded from the analysis.”

This provides:

  • The exact formulation of the probe,

  • Its position in the sequence of measures (it follows the happiness questions, as per the ordering in the same section),

  • The purpose of the check,

  • And information about its use in participant exclusion.
exclumeasure3_e: there is no evidence that time-related constraints were used as a criterion for exclusion (neither in the main text nor in the supplementary materials)
statistical_analysis_e: The authors explicitly state that they used R for statistical analysis (e.g., “All analyses were conducted in R…”). R is a specific statistical program, and its mention satisfies the criterion for answer b. This answer is appropriate even if the techniques used could fall under the simpler category described in c, because the use of a specific program is reported.
qmeasure1_e:
The article clearly states that the studies were conducted online using Amazon Mechanical Turk (MTurk),

For the expert sample, the article states:

“We also recruited a separate group of professional philosophers through email and asked them to complete the same study online.”

While the exact tool or platform used to administer the survey to experts is not specified (e.g., Qualtrics, SurveyMonkey), it is clearly described that the study was conducted online.

So, both groups (MTurk participants and experts) completed the survey online, and online administration counts as a described method of displaying stimuli, even if the specific software isn’t named.
qmeasure2_e: Both the MTurk and expert participants completed the study online, as explicitly stated in the article (e.g., “asked them to complete the same study online”). For online surveys, the specific implements (mouse, keyboard, etc.) are not typically listed, and this falls under the “not applicable” category per the coding instructions.
qmeasure3_e:
The paper provides clear and systematic information about how the stimuli (vignettes) were constructed:

  • Each agent’s scenario was presented in two moral conditions (morally good vs. morally bad), with the only difference between them being the morally relevant behavior.

  • The stimuli were designed to hold constant the agent’s emotional state and life circumstances, varying only moral valence—this is explicitly stated in the methods.

  • The structure is uniform across all vignettes (job/life situation + emotions/satisfaction + morally relevant reason), so it would be possible to generate new ones using the same formula.

  • The exact wording of all stimuli is available in the Supplementary Materials, allowing clear identification of important differences between conditions.

Thus, the construction procedure, purpose of differences, and principles for generating more stimuli are all clear.
qmeasure4_e:
The exact formulations of the probes used in Study 1 are included in the dataset (study1_mturk_data.csv) as column headers, such as:

  • happy1: “How happy is this person emotionally?”

  • happy2: “How satisfied is this person with their life overall?”

  • happy3: “How meaningful is this person’s life?”

  • happy4: “Overall, how happy is this person?”

These are direct, verbatim formulations of the probes, not paraphrases. Therefore, the paper (together with its supplementary materials and shared data) does report the exact wording of the probes used.
qmeasure5_e:
The appendix in the main article provides a detailed overview of the vignettes used in Study 1, and the supplementary materials include the full text of all six vignettes (3 agents × 2 moral conditions). These materials ensure that:

  • The entire set of stimuli is available.

  • No essential components of the vignettes are omitted.

  • A reader would be able to fully reconstruct the materials used.
qmeasure6a_e: Although the appendix describes that participants read a vignette and then rated happiness, the exact format of presentation—specifically whether the vignette and probes were shown on the same screen or page, or separately—is not explicitly stated. The information provided does not meet the threshold for a clear specification of how the stimuli and questions were presented in relation to each other.
qmeasure6b_e: Each study condition in Study 1 consists of a single vignette paired with a single probe, as described in the main text and confirmed by the supplementary materials. Since there is no set of multiple stimuli or probes per condition whose order could vary or be randomized, the question of order does not apply in this case.
qmeasure6c_e: Since only one probe was presented per vignette, the question of how many probes were shown on a single screen/page does not apply.
qmeasure6d_e: Since only one vignette and one probe were presented per participant, the issue of navigating between multiple questions or vignettes does not arise. Therefore, the question about the ability to go back is not applicable.
qmeasure6e_e: The paper and the supplementary materials do not specify whether all questions in the questionnaire were mandatory, nor do they indicate which specific questions (if any) were required. Without this information, we cannot determine whether any questions were optional.
qmeasure6f_e: There is no indication in the paper or supplementary materials that any technical measures (such as time delays, forced timing, or response constraints) were used to elicit specific behaviors. Since such measures were not used, this item is not applicable.
qmeasure7a_e:
the paper does make it clear that the comprehension check used “True” and “False” as response options.

In the “Measures” section of Study 1, it explicitly says:

“Participants were asked a comprehension question (‘Did [agent] do something good or something bad?’). If they answered incorrectly (false instead of true), they were excluded.”

The quoted terms "false" and "true" clearly indicate the exact response categories used.
qmeasure7b_e:
based on the datasets:

  • In both the expert and MTurk datasets, the happiness, positive, negative, and satisfaction variables use numerical values that appear to follow a Likert-style scale (e.g., 1 to 7 in the MTurk data, with similar usage in expert data).

  • These numbers are present in the data columns, indicating that participants were likely shown numerical labels during the survey (rather than only verbal descriptors).
qmeasure7c_e:
the Happiness Attribution and Happiness Expertise questions both used Likert-type scales with clearly specified  labels.

  1. Happiness Attribution:

“Participants were then asked how happy they thought the person really was. They responded to this question on a 7-point scale ranging from ‘not at all happy’ (1) to ‘very happy’ (7).”

  1. Happiness Expertise:

“Participants were then asked how much of an expert they were at knowing when someone is really happy. They responded on a 7-point scale ranging from ‘not at all an expert’ (1) to ‘very much an expert’ (7).”

the number of points is specified (7-point scale), both anchors are named, and the exact wording of the anchors is clearly given.
qmeasure7d_e: Neither the main article, nor the supplementary materials (including the GitHub repository and datasets), indicate how the response scale was visually presented to participants (e.g., horizontally or vertically). This detail is not described anywhere.
qmeasure8_e:
Yes, in the Supplementary Materials, specifically under the vignette presentations, additional phrasing confirms how participants were introduced to the task. For example, before each vignette, the participant sees a brief contextual sentence such as:

“Read the following story and answer the question that follows.”

This reinforces that the study instructions were indeed described, even if briefly, both in the main text and in the supplementary materials.
qmeasure9_e:
There is no mention in the main text, the Measures section, or the Supplementary Materials or Datasets of:

  • how much time was given for each probe or question,

  • whether there was a time limit on questionnaire completion,

  • or the average completion time for participants.

Thus, none of the relevant timing information is provided.
qmeasure10_e: In the description of Study 1 (Method section), it is explicitly stated that participants were randomly assigned to one of the six conditions (three characters × morally good vs. morally bad versions). This satisfies the criterion for random assignment.
flow1_e: While the article clearly reports the total number of participants included in the analysis (N = 300 lay participants for Study 1), it does not specify how many participants were initially recruited or assigned to each of the six conditions (i.e., how many participants were in each vignette group before and after exclusions). Additionally, although some exclusions are described (based on the comprehension check), the exact number of participants excluded and how many remained per group is not provided, which makes the participant flow incomplete.
flow2_e: The article does not include any flowchart, figure, or table that explicitly depicts participant flow. Although numbers of participants included in the analysis are mentioned in the text, this information is not visualized in a structured diagram or table summarizing the recruitment, exclusions, and final analyzed sample.
flow3_e: The authors report that all samples were determined a priori to have more than 95% power to detect an effect size of d = 1.603 with α = .05, based on prior research (Phillips et al., 2011).
descriptive1_e: In the Results section of Study 1, the paper provides means (M) and standard deviations (SD) for each condition, including moral/good vs. bad manipulations across agents. Additionally, for categorical variables such as the comprehension check (True/False), the number of participants answering correctly is reported. All relevant descriptive statistics are given per condition.
descriptive2_e: In the Results section of Study 1, the authors report 95% confidence intervals (CIs) alongside some of the key means (e.g., for the main happiness attribution ratings per condition), but not for all measures used in the study. For example, CIs are not systematically reported for every subgroup or every dependent measure (such as expertise ratings).
inferential1_e:
In the Results section of Study 1, the authors report inferential statistics including the test statistic (e.g., t), degrees of freedom, and p-values for all relevant t-tests. For example, they include results like:

t(402.37) = 5.20, p < .001

This reporting pattern is consistent throughout the inferential analyses presented for Study 1
inferential2_e: In the Results section of Study 1, the authors consistently report p-values in an exact format (e.g., p = .004, p = .029, p = .001), or appropriately use p < .001 when values are extremely small. There are no instances of vague reporting like p < .05 or p = .1.
inferential3_e:
In Study 1 of Phillips et al. (2017), the only standardized effect size explicitly reported is for the planned comparison between the morally bad and morally good conditions (Cohen’s d = 0.66). That’s appropriate and commendable. However, the authors also conduct several additional statistical tests for which no effect sizes are reported, even though they reasonably could (and arguably should) have been.

  • Missing: For the ANOVA (no η²), group comparison among experts (no d), and interaction term.
interpretation_e:
The paper provides a clear interpretation of how the results from Study 1 relate to the research problem and hypothesis. It states that participants judged morally good agents as significantly happier than morally bad ones and that this pattern was consistent across participant groups (nonresearchers, researchers, and happiness experts). The authors interpret these results as supporting the hypothesis that moral value influences happiness attributions and that this effect reflects a robust feature of the ordinary concept of happiness, rather than arising from misunderstanding or motivational bias:

"Taken together, the results of this study suggest that the influence of moral value on assessments of happiness is highly robust. ... the impact of moral value on assessments of happiness is unlikely to be explained as a misunderstanding of the task or a simple error on the part of participants. Rather, the effect of moral value seems to reflect a robust aspect of how people ordinarily make assessments of happiness"

Regarding statistical conclusion validity, the paper addresses this through its methodological choices. For instance, it states that:

  • They conducted linear mixed-effects models to generalize findings across participants and scenarios.

  • They included both participants and items as random effects, a method explicitly chosen to support the robustness and generalizability of statistical conclusions

  • Sample sizes were determined a priori to ensure high power (>95%) to detect the key effect (Cohen’s d = 1.603), addressing concerns about low power and effect estimationP
validity_e:
In the General Discussion and other relevant sections, the authors explicitly mention and assess the following threats:

  1. Sampling bias: The authors acknowledge that participants were from the United States and that moral beliefs (and thus judgments of happiness) may differ cross-culturally, limiting generalizability.

  2. Framing/order effects: They note that judgments about happiness might be sensitive to how scenarios are described, especially when immoral actions are involved, acknowledging a threat of framing effects.

  3. Construct underrepresentation / ambiguity: The authors also discuss that people may interpret the concept of happiness differently (e.g., subjective well-being vs. moral happiness), suggesting that the operationalization may not fully capture the construct — a threat to construct validity.

interpretation_e:
As it turns out, participants in our study were significantly less willing to agree
with the claim that Professor Smith caused the problem

Prima facie, our hypothesis was not satisfied since a comparison of the means of

validity_e:
difference. This result was surprising, but perhaps
can be explained by the suggestion that the Administrative Assistant’s behavior was
not atypical enough. That is, if her behavior was radically atypical perhaps we would
have found a statistically significant result in the mean of agreement with the claim
that she caused the problem. Furthermore, Professor Smith’s behavior was reinforced
as immoral throughout the story, whereas the Administrative Assistant’s behavior
was only discussed in brief and so perhaps this influenced the result. Notwithstanding
these suggestions, analyzed from this perspective our results appeared consistent with
Knobe and Fraser’s hypothesis that the application of the concept causation is
primarily influenced by moral judgments. However, further reflection on our
findings suggested that perhaps the atypicality did have an effect, just not as we had
predicted.

In addition, the vignettes utilized
thus far are subject to a legitimate concern, that is, perhaps we are not testing whether
moral valence plays a role at all since there is a real question whether breaking a
company policy is a moral violation.

interpretation_e:
What emerges from this study is the unsound use of folk aesthetics by
aesthetic theories. On the one hand, Aesthetic Philosophy strives to elucidate
common sense's aesthetic judgments and behaviors. On the other, claims about
common sense's aesthetic judgments and behaviors are more often grounded
on a few examples from our idiomatic expressions or, worse, on other theoretical
analysis with no empirical ground, rather than on methodologically
controlled observations.
Our study shows that a bottom-up approach, with controlled data about
aesthetic judgments made by common sense, can be very useful and provide
robust data. Yet our study is only an outline of what an empirically grounded
Aesthetic Philosophy, in which premises are warranted by controlled experiments,
can be. Indeed others studies are required: to refine data with tests
on more complex predicates, to obtain cross-cultural data, to test other
theories, etc.16
Florian
validity_e:
Some can argue that we asked participants to make judgments about
aesthetic judgments asserted by other (Active) persons and thus that par-ticipants may not have felt seriously concerned by those judgments. Maybe,
if their own aesthetic beliefs were at stake, the participants would not have
produced nonrealist answers.

One can argue that the type of aesthetic judgments we used is not
relevant or significant. In our scenarios, Agathe and Ulrich make
judgments about only one object. However in life, we do not always make
aesthetic judgments this way. We can compare things, e.g., judge that an
object is more beautiful than another. Studying such judgments could be
the true way of probing common sense's normativism. Indeed, Hume used
comparative judgments to show the absurdity of the thesis according to
which all aesthetic judgments have the same value:

Eventually, some could argue that the results of our experiments are
not representative because the participants are biased (indeed, most of
them were Parisian students). Thus, we cannot infer that our results are
valid for other populations.

Another line of objection could be that our experiments are methodologically
sound, but that they only capture people's reflexive and explicit
beliefs, not what common sense really thinks, at a deep, unconscious level,
and that is only perceivable through subtle and indirect cues. In other words,
people could utter aesthetic judgments endowed with normativity without
being explicitly normativist.
 

It is sometimes advanced against Aesthetic Skepticism that the Skeptic
contradicts himself in his actions: it is evident that we find that some objects
(or persons) are beautiful while others are not, and it is also evident that such
evaluations play a causal role in our behavior. For example: we choose this
painting for our room rather than any other because we judge it to be the most
beautiful. But, according to the Realist, if we weren't realists about aesthetic
values, we would not act this way. We would be indifferent to aesthetic values
and they shouldn't have any weight in our decision-making. So, the Skeptic
contradicts himself every time he acts upon an aesthetic evaluation.

Another argument starts with the following anthropological fact: we
try sometimes to modify the views of others about what is beautiful and
what is ugly, and we put forward our views. According to the normativist's
view, this fact would not make any sense if we did not think (i) that
aesthetic judgments have a truth-value, and (ii) that this truth-value can be
the same for different persons

In order to test whether anger responses underlie the asymmetry
in intentionality judgments seen in the SEE, we used the Trait
Anger Scale (TAS) (Spielberger, 1999) to measure participants’
propensity to feel anger along with their intentionality ratings
in the original chairman vignette

Inasmuch as the only difference between both vignettes
is the moral valence of the side-effect, it is concluded that moral
judgments influence intentionality judgments. People usually
assign intentionality for negative side effects (Harm cases), but
not for positive side effects (Help cases). This phenomenon is
known as the side-effect effect (SEE) or the Knobe effect

As the ABH states that affective reactions to the chairman
action and its outcomes explain the higher intentionality ratings
inHarm cases, but not in Help cases, we analyzed the relationship
between TAS scores and intentionality ratings in Harm and

interpretation_e:
While we replicated the SEE, we failed to find support for
the ABH: a higher disposition to get angry (as measured by
the Trait Anger Scale) was not related with higher ratings of
intentionality or blame in Harm cases
validity_e:
Considering the possibility that the Trait Anger Scale
might not be a sensitive enough measure of the involvement of
anger in these judgments, or the possibility that participants did
not experience anger at all, we devised a second study in which
we directly manipulated participants’ affective state using anger
elicitation.
There are some limitations in our studies. Regarding Study
1, Spielberger’s TAS may not be the best choice when studying
moral anger responses, and participants that scored higher in
the TAS scale might not experience higher anger reactions to
the chairman vignette. Our emotion elicitation technique has
limitations too, since there were significant differences across

groups in self-reports of emotions that were not the target of
our manipulation. In study 2, our manipulation was successful
in inducing anger on participants, but it also induced another
negative emotion, disgust. In study 3, apart from anger and
amusement, our manipulation influenced participants’ levels of
reported sadness. However, other widely-used emotion elicitation
methods suffer from the same problems. For example, film clips
selected for inducing anger also elicit significant changes in
participants’ levels of disgust and sadness (Gross and Levenson,
1995; Rottenberg et al., 2007). Furthermore, and of special
interest here, anger-inducing film clips have been successfully
used to increase participants blame attributions (Lerner et al.,
1998; Goldberg et al., 1999).

goals1_e:
In what follows, I report the results of seven new empirical studies that raise significant
challenges to blame-based explanations of the ESEE. To fix ideas, the version
of ‘the blame hypothesis’ that I will examine is comprised of the following claims:
(B1) The fact that individuals are more inclined to attribute knowledge to agents
who perform negatively valenced actions than to agents who perform neutral
or positively valenced actions represents a performance error.
(B2) The performance error consists in participants’ increased tendency to
attribute knowledge to agents who perform negatively valenced actions; participants’
lesser inclination to attribute knowledge to agents who perform
neutral or positively valenced actions does not represent an error of the kind
in question.
(B3) The performance error is due to the undue influence of a motivation to blame
agents who perform negatively valenced actions.
